WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:08.010
-Hi, welcome.

00:00:08.010 --> 00:00:09.710
I'm John Huth.

00:00:09.710 --> 00:00:13.170
I'm with the Physics Department
and also the Radcliffe

00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:15.660
Institute for Advanced Study.

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:19.130
So let me just say a few
words about Radcliffe.

00:00:19.130 --> 00:00:22.250
We have multiple programs here.

00:00:22.250 --> 00:00:27.490
And its mission is explicitly
to be cross-disciplinary,

00:00:27.490 --> 00:00:30.510
multidisciplinary,
which distinguishes it

00:00:30.510 --> 00:00:32.900
from other institutes
for advanced study.

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:37.940
And to be engaged
in this institution

00:00:37.940 --> 00:00:42.290
has been just amazing
for me because I've

00:00:42.290 --> 00:00:44.890
learned all sorts of
things that I wouldn't

00:00:44.890 --> 00:00:46.680
thought I would have learned.

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:48.930
I'm a particle
physicist by trade

00:00:48.930 --> 00:00:53.200
and I get into all sorts
of topics like the oceans,

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:55.090
for example.

00:00:55.090 --> 00:00:58.420
We have many programs that
includes a fellowship program,

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:03.600
where people can come and spend
a year here with scientists,

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:08.200
playwrights, people in
the humanities, artists.

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:12.420
There's a Schlesinger
Library and it's

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:15.960
dedicated to the history
of women in America.

00:01:15.960 --> 00:01:17.960
I'm a member of the
Ventures faculty, which

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:22.510
runs our number of programs,
including exploratory seminars,

00:01:22.510 --> 00:01:25.740
which are meant to be
interdisciplinary, workshops

00:01:25.740 --> 00:01:28.270
and science symposium.

00:01:28.270 --> 00:01:31.150
This coming year our
science symposium

00:01:31.150 --> 00:01:34.590
is on the oceans, looking
at various aspects

00:01:34.590 --> 00:01:39.480
various aspects of oceans like
the early life in the oceans,

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:43.960
where it came from, life in
hydrothermal vents for example,

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:49.060
and also the outsized role that
oceans play in our climate.

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:52.850
We also will be having
a series of lectures.

00:01:52.850 --> 00:01:56.160
The ocean's symposium
is on October 28.

00:01:56.160 --> 00:01:59.250
Our kickoff lecture
is Monday October 24

00:01:59.250 --> 00:02:04.620
by Kerry Emanuel, who is a
climatologist, meteorologist

00:02:04.620 --> 00:02:09.520
expert from MIT, who came up
with the concept of hyper cane

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:13.550
which is a hurricane that
will occur if the sea

00:02:13.550 --> 00:02:16.890
temperatures rise
about 15 degrees C,

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:20.810
and has predicted that
with the warming oceans

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:23.030
the frequency of
hurricanes will decrease

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:26.050
but their intensity will
increase tremendously.

00:02:26.050 --> 00:02:29.630
So that's on October 24.

00:02:29.630 --> 00:02:32.380
What we have here
is our kickoff event

00:02:32.380 --> 00:02:36.320
of a series that is
called Next In Science.

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:39.560
And the idea is that we're
going to bring early career

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:45.200
scientists to talk about their
work to a general audience.

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:49.480
And I guess this is
in part motivated

00:02:49.480 --> 00:02:53.160
by what I've observed that a lot
of the interesting new science

00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:57.140
is happening at the intersection
between disciplines,

00:02:57.140 --> 00:02:58.030
always has.

00:02:58.030 --> 00:03:00.790
And often times the
way universities

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:03.970
are set up with
departments, the departments

00:03:03.970 --> 00:03:05.850
can sometimes be
somewhat stovepiped

00:03:05.850 --> 00:03:08.050
and miss opportunities.

00:03:08.050 --> 00:03:11.110
And in fact, a lot
of young scientists

00:03:11.110 --> 00:03:13.970
tend to gravitate
to work that tends

00:03:13.970 --> 00:03:16.170
to be at the boundaries
of disciplines.

00:03:16.170 --> 00:03:21.250
And so in a way by exposing
Harvard and the public

00:03:21.250 --> 00:03:24.640
to their work, we are
trying to educate ourselves

00:03:24.640 --> 00:03:29.120
about new areas, emerging
areas in the sciences

00:03:29.120 --> 00:03:31.490
in addition to
getting some exposure

00:03:31.490 --> 00:03:33.470
to the young scientists.

00:03:33.470 --> 00:03:36.890
Just as an example,
in my own discipline,

00:03:36.890 --> 00:03:39.980
particle physics, which
is I would say rather

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:45.320
mature at this point, it
had its start in study--

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:48.900
well one of the starts in
experimental particle physics

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:50.680
was in the study of clouds.

00:03:50.680 --> 00:03:53.420
There are various theories
about how clouds formed.

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:55.660
One of them was accretion
around dust particles.

00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:58.530
Another was around charged
particles in the atmosphere.

00:03:58.530 --> 00:04:01.530
And cloud chambers
were invented basically

00:04:01.530 --> 00:04:02.940
to try to make clouds.

00:04:02.940 --> 00:04:06.850
And as an accidental
result, people

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:09.010
were able to find charged
particles using clouds.

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:12.740
And so there you have sort
of a funny, accidental,

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:17.060
cross-disciplinary work
that absolutely innovated

00:04:17.060 --> 00:04:19.110
the field of particle physics.

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:22.970
So as I said, we focus on
early career scientists

00:04:22.970 --> 00:04:24.930
and we try to have a theme.

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:28.180
Keeping in the theme
with the oceans,

00:04:28.180 --> 00:04:33.050
we decided to gather together
four outstanding scientists,

00:04:33.050 --> 00:04:36.130
early career scientists, to talk
about their work in the oceans.

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:38.610
And since I helped
organize this I

00:04:38.610 --> 00:04:42.117
had I guess the privilege
of picking the topics

00:04:42.117 --> 00:04:44.200
that I found the most
interesting and the speakers

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:46.099
that I found the
most interesting.

00:04:46.099 --> 00:04:47.640
Even though you
might not realize it,

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:52.010
we did a little homework
before we asked you to come.

00:04:52.010 --> 00:04:56.830
So, the format is, we'll have to
approximately 30 minute talks.

00:04:56.830 --> 00:04:58.300
Hold your questions for them.

00:04:58.300 --> 00:05:02.730
We'll then go to questions from
the audience, take a break,

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:05.950
and then come back
for two more talks.

00:05:05.950 --> 00:05:09.210
And I think they'll
be fascinating,

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:12.840
at least I'm going to be on
the edge of my seat listening.

00:05:12.840 --> 00:05:17.660
So the first speaker today
is Dr. Rachel Gittman,

00:05:17.660 --> 00:05:20.850
who is from the Marine
Science Center at Northeastern

00:05:20.850 --> 00:05:24.640
University and got her doctorate
at the University of North

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:27.590
Carolina at Chapel
Hill and is going

00:05:27.590 --> 00:05:31.930
to talk on the
subject of shorelines.

00:05:31.930 --> 00:05:35.040
I'll just say some words
about why I get interested

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:37.920
in these things, but since
I'm not a sea kayaker,

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:39.600
I spend a lot of
time on the coast

00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:42.240
and I'm always looking
at the dynamics of what's

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:44.640
happening when shorelines
and why the sands going away

00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:48.760
here and going over
there, and also pondering

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:52.000
why some large jetty
is cracking apart

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.810
and the sand is all disappearing
behind that jetty which

00:05:54.810 --> 00:05:59.290
was supposed to hold back
the sand from erosion.

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:04.590
And so Rachel is going
to talk about this topic.

00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:07.630
And the title of her talk
is Living Shorelines: Are We

00:06:07.630 --> 00:06:11.401
Designing Functional Sustainable
and Resilient Coasts.

00:06:11.401 --> 00:06:11.900
Rachel.

00:06:11.900 --> 00:06:12.950
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:17.254 --> 00:06:19.170
-Thank you for that
introduction and thank you

00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:21.000
all for coming today.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.220
So just a little
background since this

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:24.690
is kind of a diverse group.

00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:26.050
I'm an ecologist by training.

00:06:26.050 --> 00:06:28.566
I'm going to start kind
of with some ecology

00:06:28.566 --> 00:06:30.690
and because this is an
interdisciplinary talk, kind

00:06:30.690 --> 00:06:35.290
of move into a tiny, tiny
bit of the engineering side

00:06:35.290 --> 00:06:38.830
and then into some
social science.

00:06:38.830 --> 00:06:42.760
So our coastlines are incredibly
diverse, not just in the US,

00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:44.090
but globally.

00:06:44.090 --> 00:06:46.280
They can encompass
your ocean shorelines,

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:49.730
like your sand beaches,
your rocky shores, and also

00:06:49.730 --> 00:06:53.490
your sheltered coastlines,
like your coastal tidal marshes

00:06:53.490 --> 00:06:55.460
and also mangroves.

00:06:55.460 --> 00:06:58.090
And they're incredibly
valuable systems.

00:06:58.090 --> 00:07:01.680
So they encompass only
about 4% of the actual land

00:07:01.680 --> 00:07:03.870
on the earth, but
they're extremely

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:07.200
valuable in terms of their goods
and services that they provide.

00:07:07.200 --> 00:07:11.620
So there's been several studies
looking at ecosystem services

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:13.742
provided by our coastlines.

00:07:13.742 --> 00:07:15.450
And they just come
out disproportionately

00:07:15.450 --> 00:07:20.480
above a lot of our other
terrestrial ecosystems.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:23.490
And one of these services
that I think about a lot

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:27.300
is this service of providing
habitat to marine organisms.

00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:32.260
And so our coastal habitats such
as mangroves, marshes, and also

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:35.430
our open coast shore alliance,
they really serve as a nursery.

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:38.230
They serve as a habitat
through all life history

00:07:38.230 --> 00:07:40.810
stages for lots of
marine organisms.

00:07:40.810 --> 00:07:42.460
And most importantly
for people they

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:45.700
serve as habitat for a lot of
commercially and recreationally

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:47.320
valuable fish.

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:50.820
So you might recognize, if
you're from New England, cod.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:52.980
Cod actually spend some
of their life history

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:56.040
in shallow, rocky,
cobble bottom habitats,

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:58.150
also sea grass habitats.

00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:00.660
This fish is actually really
famous in North Carolina,

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:03.390
the red drum or red fish
also in the Gulf Coast.

00:08:03.390 --> 00:08:05.400
Spends a lot of its
early life history

00:08:05.400 --> 00:08:07.840
in sea grasses and marshes.

00:08:07.840 --> 00:08:11.180
And these are some juveniles of
speckled trout, Black Sea bass,

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:14.380
and also snapper that are
often pulled right out

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:18.602
of some really tidally shallow
salt marshes in North Carolina.

00:08:18.602 --> 00:08:19.810
And then I throw this one in.

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:21.226
This is actually
in the Galapagos.

00:08:21.226 --> 00:08:23.410
These are Bacalao or grouper.

00:08:23.410 --> 00:08:24.980
They actually, in
their early life

00:08:24.980 --> 00:08:26.970
history stages are
using mangrove habitats

00:08:26.970 --> 00:08:27.870
in the Galapagos.

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:32.640
So, globally, these habitats,
these near shore habitats,

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:34.590
are incredibly important
for our fisheries.

00:08:34.590 --> 00:08:35.809
They're highly productive.

00:08:35.809 --> 00:08:38.902
In the US alone,
roughly 75% of all

00:08:38.902 --> 00:08:41.110
of the fishes that are
commercially or recreationally

00:08:41.110 --> 00:08:45.380
harvested depend on estuarine
or these shallow, near shore

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:49.810
habitats at one or more of
their life history stages.

00:08:49.810 --> 00:08:52.470
So these habitats are
incredibly valuable

00:08:52.470 --> 00:08:54.430
but they're also imperiled.

00:08:54.430 --> 00:08:59.090
So we've seen unprecedented
degradation and loss

00:08:59.090 --> 00:09:01.880
of our vegetated near
coastal habitats.

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:04.330
From a quarter to
nearly half of these

00:09:04.330 --> 00:09:06.310
habitats globally
have been lost.

00:09:06.310 --> 00:09:07.970
And we've even
seen greater losses

00:09:07.970 --> 00:09:11.250
with some of our reefs, our
shellfish reefs, like oysters

00:09:11.250 --> 00:09:13.120
and also our coral reefs.

00:09:13.120 --> 00:09:15.950
And there's a number of
factors at play here.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:19.540
So you'll hear about climate
change in the talks today,

00:09:19.540 --> 00:09:21.799
but you also need
to think about all

00:09:21.799 --> 00:09:23.840
of the other human factors
that are at play here.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:26.310
And coastal development is
one that I think about a lot

00:09:26.310 --> 00:09:28.370
because we are right
along the coast.

00:09:28.370 --> 00:09:31.170
And I'd like to put this slide
up because this is actually,

00:09:31.170 --> 00:09:32.070
this is Dubai.

00:09:32.070 --> 00:09:35.450
So not only are they
developing their coastline,

00:09:35.450 --> 00:09:37.560
they're actually
creating coastline

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:40.650
to then provide
waterfront development.

00:09:40.650 --> 00:09:43.957
So they're dredging up the
sand and building islands

00:09:43.957 --> 00:09:45.790
so that people can have
waterfront property.

00:09:45.790 --> 00:09:49.920
So you can imagine that that
has pretty dire ecological, also

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:54.650
physical consequences for those
coastlines and those habitats.

00:09:54.650 --> 00:09:57.070
And so we might say,
well, that's Dubai.

00:09:57.070 --> 00:09:58.610
We don't do that
kind of thing here.

00:09:58.610 --> 00:10:00.600
But that's actually not true.

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:04.680
This is actually a shot I
took flying into Logan on one

00:10:04.680 --> 00:10:06.640
of my trips back up to Boston.

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:09.170
And you know, it's a pretty
densely populated coastline,

00:10:09.170 --> 00:10:09.669
right?

00:10:09.669 --> 00:10:13.030
So New England's got a lot of
people and we love our coast.

00:10:13.030 --> 00:10:15.200
Everyone loves Cape Cod.

00:10:15.200 --> 00:10:18.630
And these resources
are valued just

00:10:18.630 --> 00:10:20.240
for recreation and tourism.

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:22.180
But obviously having
this many people

00:10:22.180 --> 00:10:25.450
living along the coastline can
have some real consequences

00:10:25.450 --> 00:10:28.060
for those ecosystems.

00:10:28.060 --> 00:10:31.700
Now in a natural setting
devoid of people,

00:10:31.700 --> 00:10:34.560
there are a fair number
of stressors that occur

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:36.420
for these coastal ecosystems.

00:10:36.420 --> 00:10:39.790
This is actually a salt
marsh in North Carolina.

00:10:39.790 --> 00:10:41.560
And this is a core sound.

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:43.010
So it's a pretty large sound.

00:10:43.010 --> 00:10:45.690
It's shallow, but when
you get the wind blowing

00:10:45.690 --> 00:10:48.050
from the right direction,
the fetch is very large

00:10:48.050 --> 00:10:50.690
or the distance across
the sound is fairly large.

00:10:50.690 --> 00:10:52.970
And you'll get a significant
amount of wave energy

00:10:52.970 --> 00:10:55.920
hitting these coastal
habitats these marshes.

00:10:55.920 --> 00:10:59.710
And so they erode over time and
they essentially roll back up

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:01.330
into the uplands as they erode.

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:04.870
And so this is a
dynamic, natural process.

00:11:04.870 --> 00:11:06.090
Shorelines erode.

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:07.420
They move around.

00:11:07.420 --> 00:11:10.890
As John was kind of alluding
to, sand is not static.

00:11:10.890 --> 00:11:12.422
It's not staying in one place.

00:11:12.422 --> 00:11:13.880
And so this is not
really something

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.630
we're concerned
about as scientists,

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:19.040
that we have erosion
or that this marsh is

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:20.430
going to flood at high tide.

00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:22.350
These are all natural processes.

00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:27.780
It's really when we have kind of
the loss of these habitats then

00:11:27.780 --> 00:11:31.000
tied to human infrastructure
that people really

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:32.297
start to worry about it.

00:11:32.297 --> 00:11:34.630
Because these systems are
going to persist through time,

00:11:34.630 --> 00:11:36.720
geologic history has shown us.

00:11:36.720 --> 00:11:37.850
We still have salt marshes.

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:39.960
We're going to continue
to have salt marshes.

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:42.780
But it's really when
we as humans, come in

00:11:42.780 --> 00:11:44.670
and we draw a line in
the sand, and we say,

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:47.050
this is my waterfront property.

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:49.590
I want it to stay
here for my lifetime

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:50.840
that we start to see an issue.

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:52.430
And this is a picture I took.

00:11:52.430 --> 00:11:54.160
This is in Dauphin
Island, Alabama.

00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:57.230
So people have decided that
they want to live right

00:11:57.230 --> 00:12:01.230
on the water, and over time, the
ocean has eroded away the sand

00:12:01.230 --> 00:12:03.290
and their house is going
to fall in the water.

00:12:03.290 --> 00:12:05.145
And this is actually
not inhabited anymore.

00:12:05.145 --> 00:12:07.270
There's caution tape,
they're not allowed to go in.

00:12:07.270 --> 00:12:09.010
And this is up and
down the coast.

00:12:09.010 --> 00:12:10.540
It's not just from
hurricanes, it's

00:12:10.540 --> 00:12:15.190
actually just poor
zoning and poor planning.

00:12:15.190 --> 00:12:17.490
And this is a picture from
New Bern, North Carolina.

00:12:17.490 --> 00:12:18.860
So this is actually last year.

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:22.830
They had a tremendous amount
of rainfall in the fall.

00:12:22.830 --> 00:12:26.590
And then you also tend to have
these really high, high tides

00:12:26.590 --> 00:12:28.970
or king tides in the fall.

00:12:28.970 --> 00:12:32.790
And so this is just a normal day
where the high tide has come in

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:35.250
and completely flooded
the downtown area.

00:12:35.250 --> 00:12:37.540
And this is a pretty
regular occurrence now.

00:12:37.540 --> 00:12:38.780
And this happens in Boston.

00:12:38.780 --> 00:12:41.740
It happens in cities
throughout the East Coast.

00:12:41.740 --> 00:12:45.560
So that's why we have to
kind of take a step back

00:12:45.560 --> 00:12:48.430
and say, OK, we're doing
all of this development.

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:50.880
We want to live along the coast.

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:52.930
Over a third of the
global population

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:55.010
lives within 100
kilometers of the coast,

00:12:55.010 --> 00:12:56.940
and people are moving
towards the coasts.

00:12:56.940 --> 00:12:59.580
So these numbers are
going to increase.

00:12:59.580 --> 00:13:03.840
What can we really do or how
can we live along the coast

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:06.430
and also protect
this infrastructure?

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:10.850
Well, historically, what we
have done at least, the last,

00:13:10.850 --> 00:13:14.320
I would say 100,
150 years in the US,

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:16.060
has been to harden
the shoreline.

00:13:16.060 --> 00:13:18.680
So the US Army
Corps of Engineers,

00:13:18.680 --> 00:13:21.450
they have done tremendous
things in our country

00:13:21.450 --> 00:13:24.940
in terms of redirecting
rivers and also

00:13:24.940 --> 00:13:26.110
hardening our shorelines.

00:13:26.110 --> 00:13:28.140
They build these sea walls.

00:13:28.140 --> 00:13:29.830
They'll build
groins and jetties,

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:32.710
the big shore perpendicular
rock structures

00:13:32.710 --> 00:13:35.220
you often see at inlets.

00:13:35.220 --> 00:13:37.450
The idea is that you'll
engineer your way out

00:13:37.450 --> 00:13:39.670
of this problem of
coastal hazards,

00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:42.329
this problem the erosion,
or this problem of flooding.

00:13:42.329 --> 00:13:44.370
And so that's really what
we've done in the past.

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:45.732
We built sea walls.

00:13:45.732 --> 00:13:48.640
This is one actually,
at Linshore Drive,

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:51.350
so up near Swanstat,
if you know that area.

00:13:51.350 --> 00:13:53.360
This is a riprap or revetment.

00:13:53.360 --> 00:13:56.960
So it's just essentially rock
piled up along the shore.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:14:00.400
And then this is actually a
break water, so again rock

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:03.850
and in this case, it's
actually morrel actually placed

00:14:03.850 --> 00:14:06.050
seaward of a tidal salt marsh.

00:14:06.050 --> 00:14:09.030
And so, I'll actually talk
about these structures

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:11.910
in the terms of calling them a
living shoreline a little bit

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:12.800
later in the talk.

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:15.170
But these are the two
more traditional types

00:14:15.170 --> 00:14:20.180
of hardening that I really
focus on with my work.

00:14:20.180 --> 00:14:24.230
So in starting to think about
this issue, when I was starting

00:14:24.230 --> 00:14:26.350
graduate school I
wanted to do work

00:14:26.350 --> 00:14:29.420
on understanding
the ecology or what

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:31.800
was happening when you
harden the shoreline

00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:33.232
to these near shore habitats.

00:14:33.232 --> 00:14:34.940
The first question I
really had was well,

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:36.155
how much does this happen?

00:14:36.155 --> 00:14:37.530
How much hardening
do we actually

00:14:37.530 --> 00:14:39.300
have in the United States?

00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:42.010
I thought this would be an easy
number that I could look up.

00:14:42.010 --> 00:14:44.200
It turns out we had no idea.

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:46.660
So after scouring
a lot of data sets,

00:14:46.660 --> 00:14:48.080
I actually came
across a NOAA data

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:51.280
set that was used for oil spill
response where they classified

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:54.100
different shoreline types, but
they had never actually thought

00:14:54.100 --> 00:14:56.840
to do the math and to actually
figure out how much of this

00:14:56.840 --> 00:14:58.950
was actually
artificial shoreline.

00:14:58.950 --> 00:15:01.290
And so I did that
essentially for them.

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:03.770
And so what I
found is that well,

00:15:03.770 --> 00:15:07.330
if we just take a
subset of this shoreline

00:15:07.330 --> 00:15:09.070
and you look just
at New England,

00:15:09.070 --> 00:15:12.110
I figured out that about 10% of
the shoreline from Connecticut

00:15:12.110 --> 00:15:14.130
to Maine is hardened.

00:15:14.130 --> 00:15:17.130
And so this is a map
showing the warm colors

00:15:17.130 --> 00:15:19.310
being a higher percentage
of the shoreline that's

00:15:19.310 --> 00:15:21.880
actually hardened relative to
the total amount of shoreline.

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:23.102
Cool colors being less.

00:15:23.102 --> 00:15:24.560
It shouldn't really
be any surprise

00:15:24.560 --> 00:15:28.640
that the Boston area is
fairly highly hardened.

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:32.870
And if you look at the US
as a whole, it's roughly 14%

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:33.800
of the US coastline.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:37.960
This is about 22,000 kilometers,
roughly 14,000 miles.

00:15:37.960 --> 00:15:40.390
And I had a colleague actually
say that it's essentially

00:15:40.390 --> 00:15:43.166
like saying, you could
take one in six steps

00:15:43.166 --> 00:15:45.040
and you could encounter
a hardened shoreline,

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:48.511
which I thought was a kind of
neat way to think about it.

00:15:48.511 --> 00:15:50.930
So 14% might not seem
like a whole lot,

00:15:50.930 --> 00:15:53.850
but when you think about how
much coast we actually have,

00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:55.450
it's a pretty
substantial number.

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:58.320
And it's likely to increase,
given the number of people

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:00.770
that are moving to the coasts.

00:16:00.770 --> 00:16:02.630
So I did a series
of analyzes to kind

00:16:02.630 --> 00:16:05.000
of figure out what's most
correlated with shoreline

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:05.980
hardening.

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:07.980
And it's no surprise
that you know,

00:16:07.980 --> 00:16:09.719
housing density is
positively correlated

00:16:09.719 --> 00:16:10.760
with shoreline hardening.

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:13.320
The more people you have,
the more houses you have,

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:15.260
the more hardening you have.

00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:17.880
So if you look at predictions
for population growth,

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:20.080
what we see is that really
it's the South Atlantic

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:22.010
and the Gulf Coast
are predicted to see

00:16:22.010 --> 00:16:24.210
the largest increases
in population

00:16:24.210 --> 00:16:26.100
in the coming decades.

00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:28.814
So we expect these
areas to be probably

00:16:28.814 --> 00:16:30.980
the ones that are going to
get hardened the quickest

00:16:30.980 --> 00:16:33.250
unless coastal management
policies change.

00:16:33.250 --> 00:16:37.045
The Northeast, we have seen
kind of natural rocky shores,

00:16:37.045 --> 00:16:39.420
and a lot of the area has
actually already been developed

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:40.461
and are already hardened.

00:16:40.461 --> 00:16:44.160
So we're probably reaching some
kind of plateau in hardening.

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:46.390
But it's these areas that
are relatively undeveloped

00:16:46.390 --> 00:16:49.760
now that we really
need to be focused on.

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:52.600
So why do we care if we're
hardening the shoreline?

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:54.189
It's essentially
just a different type

00:16:54.189 --> 00:16:54.980
of shoreline right?

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:58.200
We're using hard materials.

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:00.580
What does it do in terms of
providing functional habitat?

00:17:00.580 --> 00:17:04.000
Is it equivalent to having
a marsh shoreline or just

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.800
a natural rocky shoreline?

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:10.650
Is it equivalent in terms
of providing fish habitat?

00:17:10.650 --> 00:17:12.579
So this is a question
that I really wanted

00:17:12.579 --> 00:17:14.609
to ask kind of the last year.

00:17:14.609 --> 00:17:17.490
And so what I did was I
did a meta-analysis of all

00:17:17.490 --> 00:17:20.640
the peer-reviewed studies on
shoreline hardening in terms

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:24.220
of measuring the biodiversity
of those shoreline types,

00:17:24.220 --> 00:17:26.859
so the number and
types of organisms,

00:17:26.859 --> 00:17:29.100
and the overall
abundance of organisms

00:17:29.100 --> 00:17:31.770
on hardened shorelines
and then compared them

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:32.870
to natural shorelines.

00:17:32.870 --> 00:17:35.230
So those are all the
studies that have ever

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:37.210
been published globally.

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:40.380
So it's not just US studies
but also a lot of work

00:17:40.380 --> 00:17:42.720
out of Europe and
also Australia.

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:45.370
And the three types of
shorelines I focused on were

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:47.350
are the ones that are
most commonly used.

00:17:47.350 --> 00:17:50.000
So sea walls and bulkheads,
these are vertical walls.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.260
They're made of
concrete, wood, vinyl,

00:17:52.260 --> 00:17:54.520
depends on where you are.

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:57.310
Riprap or revetment, so it's
some type of rock or concrete

00:17:57.310 --> 00:17:58.950
piled along the shore.

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:01.180
And then these breakwaters
that can sometimes

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:04.370
include some kind of
marsh, but sometimes not.

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:07.180
And so I categorize them
into these three groups

00:18:07.180 --> 00:18:10.110
and then I took all of
the data from the studies

00:18:10.110 --> 00:18:14.420
to determine what the overall
effect was on biodiversity,

00:18:14.420 --> 00:18:17.260
and also just the total
number of organisms

00:18:17.260 --> 00:18:20.620
occupying these habitat.

00:18:20.620 --> 00:18:22.820
And so this is just a
table showing the number

00:18:22.820 --> 00:18:25.040
of studies and the
responses by category

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:27.430
for biodiversity and abundance.

00:18:27.430 --> 00:18:29.170
And this is just to
give you a visual

00:18:29.170 --> 00:18:31.520
of the types of organisms
we're talking about.

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:35.140
So I had five different kind
of categories of organisms.

00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:38.730
So flora are these
plants, so effect

00:18:38.730 --> 00:18:42.460
on the actual marsh or sea
grass or mangrove habitat.

00:18:42.460 --> 00:18:46.050
Epibiota is anything that's
growing directly on the shores.

00:18:46.050 --> 00:18:49.640
So you might have or oysters,
ribbed mussels, barnacles,

00:18:49.640 --> 00:18:51.360
tuna kits, anything
that's actually

00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:53.270
attaching to the surface.

00:18:53.270 --> 00:18:57.400
Shore birds, so any kind of
marine or shore-based bird,

00:18:57.400 --> 00:19:01.740
sea gulls, plovers, anything
dependent on shore habitat.

00:19:01.740 --> 00:19:06.340
Nekton is really mobile
fishes and crustations, so

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:09.116
your decapods, your
crabs also any fish that

00:19:09.116 --> 00:19:10.240
might be using the habitat.

00:19:10.240 --> 00:19:12.020
And then benthic
infauna is a whole suite

00:19:12.020 --> 00:19:14.450
of organisms actually
living in the sediments.

00:19:14.450 --> 00:19:18.185
So it can be bivalves,
gastropods, also polychaetes.

00:19:20.790 --> 00:19:23.660
So I'm going to show
you a series of graphs

00:19:23.660 --> 00:19:27.140
here on biodiversity and
abundance of effects.

00:19:27.140 --> 00:19:29.230
And so all you really
need to understand

00:19:29.230 --> 00:19:31.910
here is that this is a
measure of effect size.

00:19:31.910 --> 00:19:34.730
And the more
negative on this axis

00:19:34.730 --> 00:19:37.770
means the larger
the negative effect

00:19:37.770 --> 00:19:40.510
on biodiversity and
abundance, so the worse it

00:19:40.510 --> 00:19:42.710
is for biodiversity
and abundance.

00:19:42.710 --> 00:19:46.590
And this is for seawalls first,
riprap, and then breakwaters.

00:19:46.590 --> 00:19:48.630
And I'm just going to
highlight seawalls here.

00:19:48.630 --> 00:19:51.060
Because there are
this is the group

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:54.740
of structures that had a
significant negative effect

00:19:54.740 --> 00:19:56.380
on biodiversity and abundance.

00:19:56.380 --> 00:19:58.790
So across all of
the studies that I

00:19:58.790 --> 00:20:00.940
was able to compile
data from, we

00:20:00.940 --> 00:20:04.950
had a consistent negative
effect of this type of structure

00:20:04.950 --> 00:20:08.060
relative to a natural shoreline
on the overall ecosystem

00:20:08.060 --> 00:20:10.170
biodiversity and abundance.

00:20:10.170 --> 00:20:12.590
And if this kind of
log response ratio

00:20:12.590 --> 00:20:15.840
is not that intuitive to you,
another way to think about it

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:19.040
is a difference, a percent
difference in the biodiversity

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:20.040
in abundance.

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:22.320
And so you're essentially
talking about a little

00:20:22.320 --> 00:20:29.610
over a 25% loss in biodiversity,
and also around a 35% to 40%

00:20:29.610 --> 00:20:30.530
loss in abundance.

00:20:30.530 --> 00:20:32.800
This is biodiversity
and this is abundance

00:20:32.800 --> 00:20:35.840
when you have a sea wall
instead of a natural shoreline

00:20:35.840 --> 00:20:38.470
like a rocky shoreline
or a marsh shoreline.

00:20:38.470 --> 00:20:40.480
The other two structure
types, we did not

00:20:40.480 --> 00:20:41.660
have a significant effect.

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:44.270
They were not different
from natural shoreline.

00:20:44.270 --> 00:20:48.820
But I will say that this is
actually likely due to there

00:20:48.820 --> 00:20:50.240
being fewer number of studies.

00:20:50.240 --> 00:20:54.290
So we didn't have enough studies
to really definitively say

00:20:54.290 --> 00:20:56.654
whether or not they
are different or not.

00:20:56.654 --> 00:20:58.570
And so I'm hoping we'll
see more work come out

00:20:58.570 --> 00:20:59.440
in the coming years.

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:02.110
So the jury's still kind
of out on these other types

00:21:02.110 --> 00:21:04.210
of shorelines.

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:06.900
So just to give you an
idea of who's affected,

00:21:06.900 --> 00:21:09.810
so I mentioned the
benthic infauna.

00:21:09.810 --> 00:21:12.030
And I just list a couple
of examples studies,

00:21:12.030 --> 00:21:14.600
but it's really either
polychaete anthropods and also

00:21:14.600 --> 00:21:18.120
these filter-feeding
bivalves, clams, mussels,

00:21:18.120 --> 00:21:21.760
that kind of thing that
are living in the sediment.

00:21:21.760 --> 00:21:25.010
Shore birds are negatively
affected by sea walls,

00:21:25.010 --> 00:21:28.020
likely because when you
have a seawall in place,

00:21:28.020 --> 00:21:30.620
the beach often goes away
in front of the seawall.

00:21:30.620 --> 00:21:35.470
And these shore birds depend on
that shallow, inner tidal zone,

00:21:35.470 --> 00:21:39.910
that swash zone to feed
on benthic invertebrates.

00:21:39.910 --> 00:21:43.620
And then Nekton or your fish and
crustaceans are also affected.

00:21:43.620 --> 00:21:46.210
And these are largely
organisms that

00:21:46.210 --> 00:21:50.620
are utilizing salt marsh habitat
and also seagrass habitat.

00:21:50.620 --> 00:21:53.740
So when you lose that marsh
habitat or you replace it

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:56.830
with a bulkhead or a
seawall, you're often

00:21:56.830 --> 00:21:59.810
losing these marsh
residents like mummichogs,

00:21:59.810 --> 00:22:04.070
or the little marsh
killifish, or panaeid shrimp,

00:22:04.070 --> 00:22:07.420
so shrimp that we like to
eat, and also blue crabs

00:22:07.420 --> 00:22:09.660
from the Southeast,
so organisms that

00:22:09.660 --> 00:22:12.420
are very dependent on that
vegetative structured habitat

00:22:12.420 --> 00:22:17.120
tend to suffer when you
bulkhead a shoreline.

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:21.219
But it's not just that snapshot
biodiversity and abundance

00:22:21.219 --> 00:22:22.010
that we care about.

00:22:22.010 --> 00:22:25.270
We're also concerned about
the long term consequences

00:22:25.270 --> 00:22:27.420
of armoring the shoreline.

00:22:27.420 --> 00:22:29.240
So typically, when
you have a-- this

00:22:29.240 --> 00:22:31.600
is a typical shoreline
for the Southeast

00:22:31.600 --> 00:22:35.130
or maybe for the tidal creeks
and the marshes up in New

00:22:35.130 --> 00:22:38.220
England, you're going to have
a shallow sloping tidal marsh,

00:22:38.220 --> 00:22:41.270
a shallow water refuge, and
then maybe some sea grass

00:22:41.270 --> 00:22:44.730
here, occupied by lots of
juvenile fish and crustaceans,

00:22:44.730 --> 00:22:46.430
shore birds, and whatnot.

00:22:46.430 --> 00:22:48.390
When you put a
bulkhead in place,

00:22:48.390 --> 00:22:49.950
even though it's
permit to actually

00:22:49.950 --> 00:22:53.720
be landward of this
marsh, we're facing things

00:22:53.720 --> 00:22:56.940
like sea level rise
and also just increased

00:22:56.940 --> 00:22:58.760
severity of storm events.

00:22:58.760 --> 00:23:01.070
And so over time,
you essentially

00:23:01.070 --> 00:23:03.610
lose that marsh because
this bulkhead is not

00:23:03.610 --> 00:23:05.160
absorbing energy.

00:23:05.160 --> 00:23:07.450
It's essentially
reflecting it back.

00:23:07.450 --> 00:23:11.160
And so you get a deepening of
that intertidal environment

00:23:11.160 --> 00:23:13.044
through scour of the sediment.

00:23:13.044 --> 00:23:14.960
And engineers have known
this for a long time.

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:17.550
They actually typically pile
of rock in front of bulkheads

00:23:17.550 --> 00:23:19.760
now to prevent that tow scour.

00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:22.590
So this is not new
knowledge, but it's

00:23:22.590 --> 00:23:25.300
something that's been really
hard to document in terms

00:23:25.300 --> 00:23:29.550
of loss of marsh and sea grass
and other vegetative habitats,

00:23:29.550 --> 00:23:33.090
which is why it's actually
still permitted in the US,

00:23:33.090 --> 00:23:35.940
even though wetlands
are federally protected.

00:23:35.940 --> 00:23:38.210
So this is something that
a lot of colleagues of mine

00:23:38.210 --> 00:23:40.040
are trying to document
now, because it

00:23:40.040 --> 00:23:44.180
happens over decade scales, as
opposed to just the one or two

00:23:44.180 --> 00:23:47.650
years that you typically get
funding for a research project.

00:23:47.650 --> 00:23:50.860
And so right now I think we
have about 10 to 15 years

00:23:50.860 --> 00:23:53.200
worth of data on a
set of shorelines,

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:55.810
and I'm hoping that we'll
be able to publish something

00:23:55.810 --> 00:23:59.710
in the near future to kind
of document this loss.

00:23:59.710 --> 00:24:02.410
But the really important
part about understanding

00:24:02.410 --> 00:24:05.220
this process is this is
happening below the high water

00:24:05.220 --> 00:24:09.540
line, which is really typically
public trust resources.

00:24:09.540 --> 00:24:14.110
So these are areas that are
owned by the general public,

00:24:14.110 --> 00:24:16.860
and not by the
private property owner

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:19.700
or developer that's actually
put in that structure.

00:24:19.700 --> 00:24:25.850
So there's a very complicated
private-public ownership issue

00:24:25.850 --> 00:24:26.620
here at stake.

00:24:26.620 --> 00:24:29.320
And that's why the politics
and the policies around crystal

00:24:29.320 --> 00:24:32.710
management can be
fairly complicated.

00:24:32.710 --> 00:24:35.160
So I kind of hold
you the bad side.

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:37.780
I've told you the negative
effects of shoreline hardening.

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:39.840
But there are alternatives.

00:24:39.840 --> 00:24:42.740
There are ways that we can
protect private property

00:24:42.740 --> 00:24:47.070
from these coastal hazards
without compromising

00:24:47.070 --> 00:24:47.690
the habitat.

00:24:47.690 --> 00:24:49.820
At least that's what
a lot of the NGOs

00:24:49.820 --> 00:24:53.121
and some of NOAA's
group has been trying

00:24:53.121 --> 00:24:54.620
to do in the last
couple decades has

00:24:54.620 --> 00:24:57.480
developed these types of
structures, these living

00:24:57.480 --> 00:24:59.350
shorelines.

00:24:59.350 --> 00:25:01.407
And really, when I came
into graduate school

00:25:01.407 --> 00:25:02.990
one of the first
things I wanted to do

00:25:02.990 --> 00:25:04.531
was actually test
whether or not they

00:25:04.531 --> 00:25:08.770
were functionally equivalent
to a natural or pristine

00:25:08.770 --> 00:25:09.840
shoreline.

00:25:09.840 --> 00:25:12.110
So this is a NOAA definition
for a living shoreline.

00:25:12.110 --> 00:25:14.490
But really what you
want to take from this

00:25:14.490 --> 00:25:17.620
is that it has to have some
kind of living component.

00:25:17.620 --> 00:25:20.530
There can be a structural
element, an artificial element.

00:25:20.530 --> 00:25:23.750
You can have rocks out,
but you have to have marsh.

00:25:23.750 --> 00:25:25.484
You have to have mangrove.

00:25:25.484 --> 00:25:27.400
You have to have some
kind of living component

00:25:27.400 --> 00:25:30.210
to the shoreline for it
to be considered for NOAA

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:32.260
and for a lot of the
NOS's supporting this,

00:25:32.260 --> 00:25:34.340
a living shoreline.

00:25:34.340 --> 00:25:37.400
And here are some examples
from North Carolina

00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:39.120
for estaurine shorelines.

00:25:39.120 --> 00:25:41.220
And I should say
for the open coast,

00:25:41.220 --> 00:25:44.000
beach June grass
would be equivalent

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:47.290
if you wanted to have an
open ocean living shoreline.

00:25:47.290 --> 00:25:49.650
So this is a morel sill
with some marsh behind it.

00:25:49.650 --> 00:25:53.660
This is a granite sill
with marsh on this side.

00:25:53.660 --> 00:25:56.087
And then this is actually
a loose oyster sill

00:25:56.087 --> 00:25:58.170
that we constructed while
I was in graduate school

00:25:58.170 --> 00:26:02.230
along a really eroded shoreline
as part of an Estaurine

00:26:02.230 --> 00:26:03.200
Research Reserve.

00:26:03.200 --> 00:26:06.170
And this over time
accululated live oyster

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:07.745
and became a living oyster reef.

00:26:10.310 --> 00:26:13.390
So for the work that I was
doing in graduate school,

00:26:13.390 --> 00:26:15.730
I really wanted
to understand, OK,

00:26:15.730 --> 00:26:18.810
we have these sill structures
we want to put out.

00:26:18.810 --> 00:26:20.000
We want to plant marsh.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:21.820
We want to create
a living shoreline.

00:26:21.820 --> 00:26:25.840
Is it really truly equivalent
to a natural shoreline?

00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:27.500
And so, this is
kind of my schematic

00:26:27.500 --> 00:26:29.784
of what a natural
estaurine shoreline would

00:26:29.784 --> 00:26:30.950
look like in North Carolina.

00:26:30.950 --> 00:26:32.085
You would have salt marsh.

00:26:32.085 --> 00:26:33.460
You'd have intertidal
oyster reef

00:26:33.460 --> 00:26:35.780
and then you'd have
some sea grass.

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:37.770
Well, in a lot of places
in North Carolina,

00:26:37.770 --> 00:26:40.510
oysters have been
degraded and largely lost.

00:26:40.510 --> 00:26:42.170
So a lot of these
fringing marshes

00:26:42.170 --> 00:26:46.280
are eroding because they don't
have this natural kind of shore

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:48.810
protection anymore in
the form of oyster reefs.

00:26:48.810 --> 00:26:52.400
So I decided to compare these
shorelines that are currently

00:26:52.400 --> 00:26:54.260
eroding and might end
up being bulkheaded

00:26:54.260 --> 00:26:56.009
because the private
property owner doesn't

00:26:56.009 --> 00:26:58.450
want their property to
erode, and compare them

00:26:58.450 --> 00:27:01.250
to this newer technique, which
is to put a rock still out

00:27:01.250 --> 00:27:02.430
in front.

00:27:02.430 --> 00:27:04.920
And then also compare it
to the traditional way,

00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:07.020
which would have been
to put a bulkhead up,

00:27:07.020 --> 00:27:09.090
and then the thought
being you would eventually

00:27:09.090 --> 00:27:10.420
lose the marsh over time.

00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:13.090
So I sampled bulkheads
for the marsh,

00:27:13.090 --> 00:27:14.900
had basically
already disappeared.

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:20.120
I sampled sills with marsh
and then marsh alone.

00:27:20.120 --> 00:27:22.160
And so this first
graph is just showing

00:27:22.160 --> 00:27:24.800
you kind of a snapshot of
some of the work that I did.

00:27:24.800 --> 00:27:26.720
But it's a catch
per unit effort.

00:27:26.720 --> 00:27:29.710
So it's basically the number
of individuals that we caught.

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:32.440
And the first graph is
just comparing our control,

00:27:32.440 --> 00:27:33.930
which is the salt
marshes that have

00:27:33.930 --> 00:27:38.830
lost that intertidal oysterie
to a marsh with that rock

00:27:38.830 --> 00:27:40.270
sill out in front.

00:27:40.270 --> 00:27:42.670
The black bars are the
number of fish we caught

00:27:42.670 --> 00:27:45.320
and the gray bars are the number
of crustacians that we caught,

00:27:45.320 --> 00:27:47.630
so blue crabs and shrimp.

00:27:47.630 --> 00:27:50.150
And what we see here is
that we actually see,

00:27:50.150 --> 00:27:52.840
not only are we providing
equivalent habitat,

00:27:52.840 --> 00:27:54.480
we're actually
seeing enhancement.

00:27:54.480 --> 00:27:56.510
So we have a higher
abundance and this also

00:27:56.510 --> 00:27:59.110
applies in terms of total
diversity of fishing

00:27:59.110 --> 00:28:02.630
crustaceans occupying these
marshes that have sills

00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:05.410
in front relative
to control marshes.

00:28:05.410 --> 00:28:07.670
And one of the
thoughts might be that

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:10.220
because these marshes typically
had oyster reef in front

00:28:10.220 --> 00:28:13.000
of them, but that those had
been lost through overharvest

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:16.260
and erosion, that that rock,
that actually colonizes

00:28:16.260 --> 00:28:18.590
oysters, is serving
as a substitute

00:28:18.590 --> 00:28:19.900
for that natural structure.

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:23.452
So would obviously not be
the same in other regions

00:28:23.452 --> 00:28:24.910
that don't have
intertidal oysters.

00:28:24.910 --> 00:28:27.243
You would be thinking about
it a little bit differently.

00:28:27.243 --> 00:28:28.980
But here it seems
to be a substitution

00:28:28.980 --> 00:28:30.950
in terms of habitat.

00:28:30.950 --> 00:28:32.470
And in terms of
who's present, we

00:28:32.470 --> 00:28:36.800
have a lot of small kind of
estuarine, marsh-dependent

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:39.220
species like mummichogs
and killifish.

00:28:39.220 --> 00:28:41.530
But we also start to see
some of the commercially

00:28:41.530 --> 00:28:43.661
and recreationally
valuable species.

00:28:43.661 --> 00:28:46.160
In North Carolina, [? retrome ?]
is extremely recreationally

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:50.260
valuable, blue crab,
speckled trout, flounder,

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:53.580
and snapper species, also
some pig fish, all of these

00:28:53.580 --> 00:28:56.180
are species that people
are actively fishing for.

00:28:56.180 --> 00:29:00.650
So it's important not only just
for the ecological function,

00:29:00.650 --> 00:29:02.610
but also for the fisheries,
kind of tying back

00:29:02.610 --> 00:29:07.140
to the original reason we
care about coastal ecosystems.

00:29:07.140 --> 00:29:08.910
Now for the second
part of the study,

00:29:08.910 --> 00:29:11.580
we decided to go ahead and
sample bulkheads as well.

00:29:11.580 --> 00:29:14.010
So these are bulkheads
without any marsh in front.

00:29:14.010 --> 00:29:17.690
Same types of marshes and
then marshes with sills.

00:29:17.690 --> 00:29:19.510
And we did a more
targeted sampling

00:29:19.510 --> 00:29:24.160
to get at these marsh-dependent
organisms, so these killifish,

00:29:24.160 --> 00:29:28.540
these smaller organisms
seem to really need marsh

00:29:28.540 --> 00:29:30.860
for them to want to
be in this habitat.

00:29:30.860 --> 00:29:33.290
And so what we see
is that again we

00:29:33.290 --> 00:29:38.500
see an enhancement, although
not significant, of fish

00:29:38.500 --> 00:29:42.290
when you add the sill in front
of the control marsh, and then

00:29:42.290 --> 00:29:45.820
a definite significant increase
relative to the bulkhead.

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:49.230
So the bulkhead has
many fewer organisms,

00:29:49.230 --> 00:29:51.490
particularly these
marsh-dependent organisms

00:29:51.490 --> 00:29:54.450
than the sill or
the control marsh.

00:29:54.450 --> 00:29:58.160
And so in the control we tend
to see some general species that

00:29:58.160 --> 00:30:00.030
are using these habitats.

00:30:00.030 --> 00:30:02.040
In the sill we tend
to see some more reef

00:30:02.040 --> 00:30:04.600
or oyster associated
species that are added.

00:30:04.600 --> 00:30:07.300
So this is starting to kind
of get at some explanation

00:30:07.300 --> 00:30:13.725
as to who is really
inhabiting these habitat.

00:30:13.725 --> 00:30:15.100
But when you get
to the bulkhead,

00:30:15.100 --> 00:30:17.820
you actually only have
your generalist species.

00:30:17.820 --> 00:30:20.125
So you essentially have
your marsh residents

00:30:20.125 --> 00:30:22.630
plus generalists,
marsh residents

00:30:22.630 --> 00:30:25.442
plus reef associated
species like sheepshead.

00:30:25.442 --> 00:30:26.900
And then when you
have the bulkhad,

00:30:26.900 --> 00:30:28.430
you go back to
generalist species.

00:30:28.430 --> 00:30:30.888
So this is kind of getting more
at the composition of who's

00:30:30.888 --> 00:30:34.090
really utilizing these habitats.

00:30:34.090 --> 00:30:36.740
So just to provide
some conclusions here,

00:30:36.740 --> 00:30:40.460
living shorelines we think so
far, not based just on the work

00:30:40.460 --> 00:30:42.400
I've done, but what
others have done,

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:45.030
can serve as better habitat
for fish and crustaceans

00:30:45.030 --> 00:30:46.572
in bulkheads.

00:30:46.572 --> 00:30:48.030
And that at least
in North Carolina

00:30:48.030 --> 00:30:49.530
where you have
intertidal oysteries,

00:30:49.530 --> 00:30:51.790
they're functionally
similar to oyster reefs

00:30:51.790 --> 00:30:56.020
in terms of forage and
refuge opportunities.

00:30:56.020 --> 00:31:00.100
So I want to shift gears now
and talk about another aspect

00:31:00.100 --> 00:31:01.772
of shorelines.

00:31:01.772 --> 00:31:03.230
And that's really
whether or not we

00:31:03.230 --> 00:31:05.190
are creating sustainable,
resilient shorelines

00:31:05.190 --> 00:31:07.710
so we might find that
these living shorelines are

00:31:07.710 --> 00:31:10.890
ecologically better
than bulkheads.

00:31:10.890 --> 00:31:12.830
But if they don't
perform in terms

00:31:12.830 --> 00:31:15.272
of providing erosion
protection, no one's

00:31:15.272 --> 00:31:16.980
actually going to want
to implement them.

00:31:16.980 --> 00:31:19.354
They're going to want to stick
with the status quo, which

00:31:19.354 --> 00:31:19.900
is bulkheads.

00:31:19.900 --> 00:31:21.330
So while I was in
graduate school,

00:31:21.330 --> 00:31:25.277
Hurricane Irene came through
North Carolina in 2011.

00:31:25.277 --> 00:31:27.360
And it was about the middle
of my graduate career,

00:31:27.360 --> 00:31:29.401
so I had sampled a lot of
sites before the storm,

00:31:29.401 --> 00:31:32.610
and I was able to go back and
sample sites after the storm.

00:31:32.610 --> 00:31:36.270
And what I did initially
was just go along the areas

00:31:36.270 --> 00:31:39.220
that I knew that were hardest
hit by the hurricane and survey

00:31:39.220 --> 00:31:41.200
first just what type
of shoreline was there,

00:31:41.200 --> 00:31:44.520
just driving along in a
boat with a GPS and a camera

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:46.400
and documenting the
type of shoreline there.

00:31:46.400 --> 00:31:49.370
So these are just regions
that I sampled and the kind.

00:31:49.370 --> 00:31:51.250
What I want to point
out here is that you

00:31:51.250 --> 00:31:52.650
have a pretty good mix.

00:31:52.650 --> 00:31:54.450
You have a lot of
natural shoreline,

00:31:54.450 --> 00:31:56.820
but you also have a lot of
hardened shoreline here.

00:31:56.820 --> 00:32:01.760
And it's mostly bulkheads, so
this is the bulkhead shoreline.

00:32:01.760 --> 00:32:03.509
And what I decided
to do was that I

00:32:03.509 --> 00:32:05.050
looked to the
engineering literature,

00:32:05.050 --> 00:32:07.341
because I'm an ecologist and
I was like how do I really

00:32:07.341 --> 00:32:10.380
quantify damage to
shoreline structures?

00:32:10.380 --> 00:32:13.270
And I came across the
engineering article that

00:32:13.270 --> 00:32:15.580
basically said they do
a visual classification

00:32:15.580 --> 00:32:17.600
and they assess whether
or not the structure

00:32:17.600 --> 00:32:21.680
is intact and performing the
function that it was intended.

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:24.990
And so they had a classification
of landward erosion,

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:26.240
which is shown here.

00:32:26.240 --> 00:32:29.240
So the structure is
intact, but the land

00:32:29.240 --> 00:32:32.040
that it's supposed to be
protecting has eroded away.

00:32:32.040 --> 00:32:34.670
So that's one
category of the image.

00:32:34.670 --> 00:32:37.060
The structure might
be intact but you have

00:32:37.060 --> 00:32:38.400
some kind of structural damage.

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:39.760
So you have pieces
of the structure

00:32:39.760 --> 00:32:41.051
that are starting to fall away.

00:32:41.051 --> 00:32:44.051
That's another category of
damage you could assess.

00:32:44.051 --> 00:32:45.050
You could have a breach.

00:32:45.050 --> 00:32:47.190
So the structure is still
there, but it's actually

00:32:47.190 --> 00:32:51.320
compromised in some way
and the erosion of the land

00:32:51.320 --> 00:32:53.410
is actually occurring
behind the structure.

00:32:53.410 --> 00:32:55.740
And then you can have a
complete failure or a collapse.

00:32:55.740 --> 00:32:57.397
And so this is
what was shown here

00:32:57.397 --> 00:32:58.980
where the bulkhead
itself has actually

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:03.920
fallen into the water and all of
the land has then eroded away.

00:33:03.920 --> 00:33:05.990
And so what this
graph is showing you

00:33:05.990 --> 00:33:08.340
is that for these
different regions

00:33:08.340 --> 00:33:11.020
how much of the
bulkheaded shoreline

00:33:11.020 --> 00:33:12.850
suffered some kind of damage.

00:33:12.850 --> 00:33:15.270
And so these three
regions really

00:33:15.270 --> 00:33:17.640
had low percentages of damage.

00:33:17.640 --> 00:33:20.290
But in this one particular area
that seemed to be hardest hit,

00:33:20.290 --> 00:33:24.510
75% of the bulkheads
had some kind of damage.

00:33:24.510 --> 00:33:26.660
And I only show bulkheads
here because none

00:33:26.660 --> 00:33:30.240
of the other types of
shoreline exhibited any damage.

00:33:30.240 --> 00:33:33.130
So the structure that was
most commonly implemented

00:33:33.130 --> 00:33:37.310
for protection was actually
the one most readily damaged

00:33:37.310 --> 00:33:38.990
in a Category 1 hurricane.

00:33:38.990 --> 00:33:40.490
And that's not even
a big hurricane.

00:33:40.490 --> 00:33:42.220
So that's not Superstorm Sandy.

00:33:42.220 --> 00:33:46.700
Irene was a blip compared to
what we saw in the Northeast.

00:33:46.700 --> 00:33:48.950
And I love to put
pictures, because I

00:33:48.950 --> 00:33:52.170
think they really kind of
sell the story even better.

00:33:52.170 --> 00:33:55.904
And these are two properties
that are roughly 500 feet away

00:33:55.904 --> 00:33:56.570
from each other.

00:33:56.570 --> 00:33:57.820
They're on the same shoreline.

00:33:57.820 --> 00:34:00.180
I've been sampling these
properties for years.

00:34:00.180 --> 00:34:03.370
This property owner, Mr.
Avery, has a bulkhead.

00:34:03.370 --> 00:34:06.110
That's just an arrow
to show for reference.

00:34:06.110 --> 00:34:08.520
Mr. Shallcross had a
living shoreline put in.

00:34:08.520 --> 00:34:10.690
This is a picture I took
one year before the storm

00:34:10.690 --> 00:34:13.400
where we actually planted
the marsh grass for him.

00:34:13.400 --> 00:34:15.929
And this is actually
right after the hurricane,

00:34:15.929 --> 00:34:18.130
so the water level
is still pretty high.

00:34:18.130 --> 00:34:19.929
His bulkhead
completely collapsed.

00:34:19.929 --> 00:34:24.480
He lost, he said, about
22 truckloads of sediment,

00:34:24.480 --> 00:34:27.420
which he then put back in
and rebuilt his bulkhead,

00:34:27.420 --> 00:34:31.760
I think for about $20,000,
even though I walked him down

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:34.060
and I showed him that
this property actually

00:34:34.060 --> 00:34:40.790
had no damage except for other
people's bulkheads and docks.

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:43.520
So the only damage Jim
really suffered with his deck

00:34:43.520 --> 00:34:47.670
was damaged by pilings,
bulkhead material washing up.

00:34:47.670 --> 00:34:50.206
So no rocks out of place.

00:34:50.206 --> 00:34:52.080
I mean the marsh actually
looks a lot better.

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:53.440
So this is obviously
a year later.

00:34:53.440 --> 00:34:55.023
The plans have grown
up, but the water

00:34:55.023 --> 00:34:57.900
is really only high because it
was still high after the storm.

00:34:57.900 --> 00:35:00.210
I showed Mr. Ackery
this property

00:35:00.210 --> 00:35:03.790
and he said that he was
trying to sell his house.

00:35:03.790 --> 00:35:07.790
And he said I will
probably be able to sell it

00:35:07.790 --> 00:35:09.950
for more if I rebuild the
bulkhead because people

00:35:09.950 --> 00:35:11.860
like bulkheads.

00:35:11.860 --> 00:35:15.030
So that's that's happened.

00:35:15.030 --> 00:35:16.970
And so, I show
you those pictures

00:35:16.970 --> 00:35:19.750
but I also wanted to make
sure, just because sometimes it

00:35:19.750 --> 00:35:23.900
can be hard to actually quantify
damage to a natural shoreline,

00:35:23.900 --> 00:35:26.840
that we weren't just
observing-- it wasn't just

00:35:26.840 --> 00:35:29.180
that we weren't able
to detect the damage

00:35:29.180 --> 00:35:31.090
that these shorelines
were experiencing.

00:35:31.090 --> 00:35:35.010
And so I had a series of natural
marsh shorelines and shorelines

00:35:35.010 --> 00:35:35.980
with a sill.

00:35:35.980 --> 00:35:38.305
So the black is the
sill and the open circle

00:35:38.305 --> 00:35:39.430
are these marsh shorelines.

00:35:39.430 --> 00:35:42.200
And I was able to
sample a year before,

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:45.070
right after, and then a
year after the hurricane.

00:35:45.070 --> 00:35:47.570
This is the surface
elevation of that site.

00:35:47.570 --> 00:35:50.014
So surface elevation is
essentially a proxy for

00:35:50.014 --> 00:35:51.180
whether or not it's eroding.

00:35:51.180 --> 00:35:52.770
If the elevation
doesn't change, it's

00:35:52.770 --> 00:35:55.600
not eroding, if it drops
it means it's eroding.

00:35:55.600 --> 00:35:58.680
We saw no change in
those sites through time.

00:35:58.680 --> 00:36:00.790
And then this is
vegetation density.

00:36:00.790 --> 00:36:03.780
So this is the actual number
of plants in the marsh.

00:36:03.780 --> 00:36:05.440
And we did see a
drop in the plants.

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:07.980
So these lines were
affected by the hurricane.

00:36:07.980 --> 00:36:10.220
But the neat part is
that particularly when

00:36:10.220 --> 00:36:13.451
you had a sill, those plants
rebounded naturally within one

00:36:13.451 --> 00:36:13.950
year.

00:36:13.950 --> 00:36:16.740
So this is really getting
more to the resilience

00:36:16.740 --> 00:36:18.250
part of the shoreline.

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:22.000
This property owner, Mr.
Shallcross, his shoreline

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:23.870
is part of this data set.

00:36:23.870 --> 00:36:26.710
He's not having to do
anything to his shoreline

00:36:26.710 --> 00:36:28.540
for it to recover
from a storm event.

00:36:28.540 --> 00:36:32.520
So it's not only that they
sustain the shoreline better

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:34.250
by preventing erosion,
but they're also

00:36:34.250 --> 00:36:38.120
more resilient in terms of
rebounding from the bulkheads.

00:36:38.120 --> 00:36:39.590
We're continuing
some of this work.

00:36:39.590 --> 00:36:41.920
I have a graduate student
at UNC that I'm currently

00:36:41.920 --> 00:36:44.670
working with, where this
was one storm event.

00:36:44.670 --> 00:36:47.170
It could have just
been the perfect storm

00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:51.590
to for marshes to do well and
for bulkheads to do poorly.

00:36:51.590 --> 00:36:54.310
So we decided that we were
going to continue this work.

00:36:54.310 --> 00:36:56.460
And she actually went out
after hurricane Arthur

00:36:56.460 --> 00:37:00.520
in 2014, another category
1 storm, slightly different

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:02.910
in that it came in
a different tide,

00:37:02.910 --> 00:37:04.790
so the storm surge
was different.

00:37:04.790 --> 00:37:06.660
It was a much
faster moving storm.

00:37:06.660 --> 00:37:09.400
So the impacts were
potentially very different.

00:37:09.400 --> 00:37:11.740
And so she's actually
analyzing these data now.

00:37:11.740 --> 00:37:13.240
But she went back
to the same places

00:37:13.240 --> 00:37:15.270
I did, did the same assessments.

00:37:15.270 --> 00:37:17.430
And we're going to see
if we see similar trends

00:37:17.430 --> 00:37:21.020
with the second hurricane.

00:37:21.020 --> 00:37:23.660
And we're combining this with
a little bit of social science.

00:37:23.660 --> 00:37:25.820
So a colleague of mine at
Northeastern University,

00:37:25.820 --> 00:37:29.310
Steven Scyphers, does a lot
of socioeconomic surveys.

00:37:29.310 --> 00:37:32.560
And so we have a grant
where we surveyed

00:37:32.560 --> 00:37:35.350
through online and
postcard mailings

00:37:35.350 --> 00:37:38.630
approximately 850 waterfront
residents in North Carolina.

00:37:38.630 --> 00:37:41.350
And we've asked them questions
about their perceptions

00:37:41.350 --> 00:37:43.740
of shoreline hardening in
terms of whether they think

00:37:43.740 --> 00:37:46.790
it's effective or durable by
type, whether it's a bulkhead,

00:37:46.790 --> 00:37:48.790
or riprap or living shoreline.

00:37:48.790 --> 00:37:50.290
And we've also asked
them to tell us

00:37:50.290 --> 00:37:54.230
how much damage they've
had, what's caused it,

00:37:54.230 --> 00:37:58.170
and what it costs them in terms
of repair and maintenance.

00:37:58.170 --> 00:38:00.910
And so we're just starting
to look at the data now.

00:38:00.910 --> 00:38:04.530
So I'm just showing you a
few graphs from the work

00:38:04.530 --> 00:38:06.300
that Carter has
really been leading.

00:38:06.300 --> 00:38:08.230
These top graphs
are the percentage

00:38:08.230 --> 00:38:12.090
of respondents that report
any kind of damage at all

00:38:12.090 --> 00:38:13.644
or any kind of maintenance cost.

00:38:13.644 --> 00:38:15.060
And then these are
the respondents

00:38:15.060 --> 00:38:17.750
that if they report
damage costs, how much,

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:20.250
and if they report
maintenance costs, how much.

00:38:20.250 --> 00:38:22.240
And so what I really
want to highlight here

00:38:22.240 --> 00:38:25.060
is that these natural
shorelines, so predominantly

00:38:25.060 --> 00:38:27.930
marsh shorelines are
lower in terms of just

00:38:27.930 --> 00:38:30.770
whether they report damage
at all or maintenance at all.

00:38:30.770 --> 00:38:33.500
So there's a lot of people
who are reporting no damage

00:38:33.500 --> 00:38:36.690
or maintenance the entire
lifetime of their shoreline.

00:38:36.690 --> 00:38:39.490
And then even if they are
reporting damage or maintenance

00:38:39.490 --> 00:38:41.240
costs, they are
significantly lower

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:44.305
than these bulkhead shorelines,
which are most common.

00:38:44.305 --> 00:38:46.680
Riprap is the other shoreling
that we're really not sure,

00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:49.640
we think riprap tends to be
more resilient than bulkheading,

00:38:49.640 --> 00:38:51.940
just because it's rock
kind of piled on shore.

00:38:51.940 --> 00:38:54.450
And so it's not suffering
from the same kind

00:38:54.450 --> 00:38:56.480
of structural failure.

00:38:56.480 --> 00:38:59.420
But we're still kind of
exploring, because many,

00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:02.740
many fewer people have riprap
shorelines in North Carolina

00:39:02.740 --> 00:39:05.480
than bulkhead shorelining.

00:39:05.480 --> 00:39:09.540
So I kind of want to finish with
kind of a thought about what

00:39:09.540 --> 00:39:11.570
it would really
take to get people

00:39:11.570 --> 00:39:12.900
to shift to living shorelines.

00:39:12.900 --> 00:39:15.260
So we've shown you the ecology.

00:39:15.260 --> 00:39:17.640
We showed you a little
bit of the engineering.

00:39:17.640 --> 00:39:19.960
We've also showed you a
little bit of the cost.

00:39:19.960 --> 00:39:24.730
But people are still
resistant to change.

00:39:24.730 --> 00:39:26.582
They like the status quo.

00:39:26.582 --> 00:39:28.290
They like what they've
known for decades.

00:39:28.290 --> 00:39:30.280
Bulkheads have been
something we've

00:39:30.280 --> 00:39:33.330
used for a long time
along our coastlines.

00:39:33.330 --> 00:39:35.340
And so this is work by
our colleague, Steven,

00:39:35.340 --> 00:39:37.520
where he's surveyed
people and asked them,

00:39:37.520 --> 00:39:40.560
would they be willing to
try a living shoreline?

00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:42.290
And initially he
just surveyed them

00:39:42.290 --> 00:39:43.840
and asked them that
simple question.

00:39:43.840 --> 00:39:47.240
And in Alabama, 60%, no way.

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:48.590
They want a bulkhead.

00:39:48.590 --> 00:39:53.180
But then he asked, well what if
we had some kind of cost share,

00:39:53.180 --> 00:39:55.750
and he varied the amount of
money that was cost shared.

00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:59.150
So the State would maybe give
you a tax credit for instance.

00:39:59.150 --> 00:40:03.100
And the remarkable part is that
people were really much more

00:40:03.100 --> 00:40:04.720
likely to consider it.

00:40:04.720 --> 00:40:08.130
40% of the people changed their
mind a little bit and said,

00:40:08.130 --> 00:40:10.030
yeah, maybe I would
be a little unsure

00:40:10.030 --> 00:40:12.370
or maybe I would be even
likely to build a living

00:40:12.370 --> 00:40:16.640
shoreline if all of
the cost wasn't on me.

00:40:16.640 --> 00:40:19.780
We did have roughly 6%
of Alabama respondents

00:40:19.780 --> 00:40:21.580
who actually went in
the other direction.

00:40:21.580 --> 00:40:22.740
And that's because
they were people

00:40:22.740 --> 00:40:24.710
who commented and believed
that they don't want

00:40:24.710 --> 00:40:28.000
the government spending
taxpayer dollars on any kind

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:28.930
of private property.

00:40:28.930 --> 00:40:32.576
So that's that 6%
that you see there.

00:40:32.576 --> 00:40:34.450
And so this is just a
picture of a conversion

00:40:34.450 --> 00:40:36.533
of a bulkhead to a living
shoreline, where they've

00:40:36.533 --> 00:40:39.160
actually not removed this
bulkhead, they've essentially

00:40:39.160 --> 00:40:41.060
filled in on top of
it and planed marsh.

00:40:41.060 --> 00:40:46.150
So this is something they're
trying with NGOs and with cost

00:40:46.150 --> 00:40:48.060
incentives in some areas.

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:50.730
And we're starting to
see some progress there.

00:40:50.730 --> 00:40:54.370
So that's kind of the positive
note I want to end on,

00:40:54.370 --> 00:40:58.800
is that living shorelines are
a viable option in some places.

00:40:58.800 --> 00:41:00.560
It's not going to
work everywhere.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:03.630
And with the right amount
of education and incentives,

00:41:03.630 --> 00:41:06.640
it's possible we could push
private property owners

00:41:06.640 --> 00:41:09.480
in the direction of
thinking about the long term

00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:12.440
sustainability and resilience
and ecological function

00:41:12.440 --> 00:41:14.760
of the shorelines,
rather than just, I

00:41:14.760 --> 00:41:17.410
want my property to stay exactly
the way it is for the next 30

00:41:17.410 --> 00:41:19.030
years.

00:41:19.030 --> 00:41:21.490
So with that I just want to
thank all of my collaborators,

00:41:21.490 --> 00:41:24.185
my co-authors, funding
sources over my graduate work

00:41:24.185 --> 00:41:25.750
and my postdoc work.

00:41:25.750 --> 00:41:28.400
And if you have more
questions, Steven

00:41:28.400 --> 00:41:30.020
has developed this
shoreline site

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:33.010
where you can actually post
your own personal experiences

00:41:33.010 --> 00:41:37.539
if you're a private homeowner to
this site with your shoreline.

00:41:37.539 --> 00:41:39.330
You can even contact
us and we can send you

00:41:39.330 --> 00:41:42.610
a camera, if you're
willing to take pictures

00:41:42.610 --> 00:41:44.150
during storm events.

00:41:44.150 --> 00:41:46.397
And we have some lab
pages and Twitter

00:41:46.397 --> 00:41:48.230
account if you want to
get in touch with me.

00:41:48.230 --> 00:41:49.220
So, thank you.

