00:44:38.500 --> 00:44:42.720
But what I will tell you about
today is two kind of stories,

00:44:42.720 --> 00:44:46.470
two different examples of
how I, with my colleagues,

00:44:46.470 --> 00:44:48.140
have been using
sounds that animals

00:44:48.140 --> 00:44:52.000
make to learn more about
endangered marine species.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:55.720
And I'll have an example about
blue whales and another example

00:44:55.720 --> 00:44:59.530
on grouper and fish, to
see how we can learn more

00:44:59.530 --> 00:45:04.350
about the populations and
use it for better management

00:45:04.350 --> 00:45:05.800
approaches.

00:45:05.800 --> 00:45:11.210
So ocean is in fact
a very noisy place,

00:45:11.210 --> 00:45:13.815
partly because sound in the
ocean travels really well.

00:45:13.815 --> 00:45:16.050
It travels much further
than light does.

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:18.930
So a lot of animals use
it then to communicate.

00:45:18.930 --> 00:45:21.430
Because it's a lot harder to
see things in the ocean than it

00:45:21.430 --> 00:45:22.990
is to hear things.

00:45:22.990 --> 00:45:28.360
And among [INAUDIBLE]
it's not just the animals

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:30.130
that are making sounds.

00:45:30.130 --> 00:45:32.680
Just about anything in and
around the ocean make sounds.

00:45:32.680 --> 00:45:34.680
So first of all, there's
lots of natural sources

00:45:34.680 --> 00:45:38.820
of sound in the ocean,
things like rain, waves,

00:45:38.820 --> 00:45:40.510
or even earthquakes.

00:45:40.510 --> 00:45:46.050
They are, let's see if
can play this for you.

00:45:46.050 --> 00:45:48.462
They're kind of intermittent
sources of sound, so.

00:45:48.462 --> 00:45:50.270
[RAINSTORM SOUNDS]

00:45:54.357 --> 00:45:55.190
Sounds like thunder.

00:45:55.190 --> 00:45:57.940
But it's really the sound of an
earthquake underwater recorded

00:45:57.940 --> 00:46:00.020
by hydrophones.

00:46:00.020 --> 00:46:03.517
And a lot of these natural
sources, what I call them,

00:46:03.517 --> 00:46:05.350
are very low frequency,
kind of low pitched,

00:46:05.350 --> 00:46:07.670
kind of like you
heard that sound.

00:46:07.670 --> 00:46:10.590
In addition to these
sounds, lots of animals

00:46:10.590 --> 00:46:13.190
make sounds, not just
whales, which are probably

00:46:13.190 --> 00:46:15.410
the ones you're
most familiar with,

00:46:15.410 --> 00:46:18.584
but also fish and invertebrates
also make a lot of sounds.

00:46:18.584 --> 00:46:20.750
So just a couple of examples
I want to play for you.

00:46:20.750 --> 00:46:22.550
I'm not going to play humpback
whale songs because everybody

00:46:22.550 --> 00:46:23.710
has heard those.

00:46:23.710 --> 00:46:26.620
But here one example, this
is a sperm whale clicking.

00:46:26.620 --> 00:46:29.620
[CLICKING]

00:46:38.120 --> 00:46:40.270
Sperm whales use these
clicks for echolocaiton,

00:46:40.270 --> 00:46:43.740
similar to what bats are doing.

00:46:43.740 --> 00:46:45.950
But then, rather than
playing you a humpback song,

00:46:45.950 --> 00:46:48.890
I want to play you
in minke whale song.

00:46:48.890 --> 00:46:50.870
And this is a minke
whale that you

00:46:50.870 --> 00:46:53.640
would hear if you went off shore
here in the Atlantic somewhere

00:46:53.640 --> 00:46:55.490
and stuck your
head in the ocean.

00:46:55.490 --> 00:46:57.199
Because, you can in
fact, if you are even

00:46:57.199 --> 00:46:59.448
swimming around or diving,
you can hear these animals.

00:46:59.448 --> 00:47:01.740
They're so loud that
you can often hear them

00:47:01.740 --> 00:47:02.950
if they're in the vicinity.

00:47:02.950 --> 00:47:04.732
[HEARTBEAT SOUNDS]

00:47:07.330 --> 00:47:10.090
Now, a couple of unique things
about this minke whale song

00:47:10.090 --> 00:47:12.150
is that actually, if you
notice, it is very long.

00:47:12.150 --> 00:47:14.375
It will just go on for a while.

00:47:14.375 --> 00:47:17.270
And I am playing
this at regular speed

00:47:17.270 --> 00:47:18.780
as it was recorded in the ocean.

00:47:18.780 --> 00:47:20.520
So this is literally
what you would

00:47:20.520 --> 00:47:22.060
hear if you go
out there and just

00:47:22.060 --> 00:47:23.932
were in the vicinity of one.

00:47:23.932 --> 00:47:26.287
[HEARTBEAT SOUNDS]

00:47:30.530 --> 00:47:33.510
And so this repetitive nature
is also one of the features

00:47:33.510 --> 00:47:35.985
that we see commonly,
particularly for baleen whales,

00:47:35.985 --> 00:47:39.980
where they're just making sounds
over and over and over again.

00:47:39.980 --> 00:47:47.170
But another interesting part,
speeding up a little bit.

00:47:47.170 --> 00:47:48.534
Sometimes they slow down.

00:47:48.534 --> 00:47:49.450
Sometimes to speed up.

00:47:49.450 --> 00:47:50.590
Sometimes they keep it constant.

00:47:50.590 --> 00:47:51.760
We don't really know why.

00:47:51.760 --> 00:47:54.195
But so as you said, this
is what minke whales here

00:47:54.195 --> 00:47:55.320
in the Atlantic sound like.

00:47:55.320 --> 00:47:56.810
If you went into
the Pacific, they

00:47:56.810 --> 00:47:58.060
sound totally different there.

00:47:58.060 --> 00:48:00.500
And this is also a common
thing I'll get to in a minute.

00:48:00.500 --> 00:48:03.083
But I just wanted to entice you
with that piece of information

00:48:03.083 --> 00:48:04.120
here.

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:07.020
But then of course another
important source of sound

00:48:07.020 --> 00:48:09.290
is us humans.

00:48:09.290 --> 00:48:14.644
Shipping is a huge contributor
to the low frequency noise.

00:48:14.644 --> 00:48:16.830
So you can hear the
propellers of boats.

00:48:20.657 --> 00:48:22.240
And so again, this
is a type of sound,

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:23.810
because they are
typically low frequency,

00:48:23.810 --> 00:48:25.310
they will travel
over long distances

00:48:25.310 --> 00:48:27.620
and can contribute
to increased noise

00:48:27.620 --> 00:48:30.150
levels across large areas.

00:48:30.150 --> 00:48:32.440
But there are other, also
anthropogenic sources,

00:48:32.440 --> 00:48:35.340
such as oil and gas exploration
that are large contributors

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:39.700
of ocean noise pollution, as are
even things that echo sounders.

00:48:39.700 --> 00:48:42.240
When you're going out fishing
and your little fish finder

00:48:42.240 --> 00:48:48.160
is on, that's loud and
noisy navy sonar, et cetera.

00:48:48.160 --> 00:48:51.470
So to listen to all
these kinds of sounds,

00:48:51.470 --> 00:48:55.000
we use a variety of
underwater recording devices.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:57.710
And since I'm mostly interested
in long term trends and changes

00:48:57.710 --> 00:49:00.500
over a long time, what
I've mostly been using

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:02.310
are autonomous
recorders that you

00:49:02.310 --> 00:49:05.370
can deploy on the ocean floor
for extended periods of time,

00:49:05.370 --> 00:49:07.100
and they just record
all the sounds

00:49:07.100 --> 00:49:10.740
over a certain bandwidth, over
a certain frequency range.

00:49:10.740 --> 00:49:13.166
And all of these devices,
they have the same features.

00:49:13.166 --> 00:49:14.790
They are fundamentally
the same things.

00:49:14.790 --> 00:49:16.590
They consist of a
hydrophone, which

00:49:16.590 --> 00:49:18.400
is an underwater microphone.

00:49:18.400 --> 00:49:22.070
They have a data logging
system of some sort, hard disk

00:49:22.070 --> 00:49:23.710
to store the data--
we have to retrieve

00:49:23.710 --> 00:49:27.070
the instruments typically to
get our data back and download

00:49:27.070 --> 00:49:28.360
them.

00:49:28.360 --> 00:49:31.130
Batteries, and so those
two factors the batteries

00:49:31.130 --> 00:49:33.930
and the hard disk
space are going

00:49:33.930 --> 00:49:35.480
to limit how long
you can actually

00:49:35.480 --> 00:49:36.987
deploy them on the ocean floor.

00:49:36.987 --> 00:49:38.570
On the left hand
side, I'm showing you

00:49:38.570 --> 00:49:43.540
this is an instrument that
we built in house at Scripps.

00:49:43.540 --> 00:49:45.807
Typically it's a
fairly large device.

00:49:45.807 --> 00:49:48.140
It's called a high frequency
acoustic recording package.

00:49:48.140 --> 00:49:51.210
And we can deploy these
instruments for up to a year,

00:49:51.210 --> 00:49:52.690
recording at very
large bandwidth,

00:49:52.690 --> 00:49:54.750
leave them in deep water.

00:49:54.750 --> 00:49:57.440
And when we retrieve
them, get information

00:49:57.440 --> 00:50:01.000
on a plethora of anthropogenic
sounds and animal sounds

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:04.855
and any other kind of geographic
or physical sounds as well.

00:50:04.855 --> 00:50:06.480
On the right hand
side, I'm showing you

00:50:06.480 --> 00:50:10.587
an example of a recorder that's
actually an off the shelf

00:50:10.587 --> 00:50:11.670
recorder you can just buy.

00:50:11.670 --> 00:50:14.253
It's actually a company here in
Massachusetts that makes them.

00:50:14.253 --> 00:50:16.802
And we've been using this for
some of the shallow water,

00:50:16.802 --> 00:50:17.635
shorter deployments.

00:50:17.635 --> 00:50:20.040
This is actually
from the grouper work

00:50:20.040 --> 00:50:21.450
that I'll be talking about.

00:50:21.450 --> 00:50:24.677
So there's a variety of
possibilities and scales

00:50:24.677 --> 00:50:26.010
in which these instruments come.

00:50:26.010 --> 00:50:30.550
But again, the idea is to get
long term records of sounds

00:50:30.550 --> 00:50:31.860
from underwater.

00:50:31.860 --> 00:50:33.410
And once we have
these records, we

00:50:33.410 --> 00:50:35.692
can learn a lot about
the actual animals

00:50:35.692 --> 00:50:36.900
that are making those sounds.

00:50:36.900 --> 00:50:40.780
We can learn a lot about
their distribution, also

00:50:40.780 --> 00:50:44.390
population structure or trends,
because most of the animals

00:50:44.390 --> 00:50:46.310
have species specific calls.

00:50:46.310 --> 00:50:49.174
Sometimes they're
even area specific.

00:50:49.174 --> 00:50:50.840
We can learn about
behavior because they

00:50:50.840 --> 00:50:52.770
produce different
calls, depending

00:50:52.770 --> 00:50:53.870
on their behavioral state.

00:50:53.870 --> 00:50:56.830
If they're hungry or if
they're looking for a mate,

00:50:56.830 --> 00:50:59.470
just like humans they're
going to say different things.

00:50:59.470 --> 00:51:01.770
And then ultimately,
we want to apply this

00:51:01.770 --> 00:51:06.440
to species management or to also
understand how us humans are

00:51:06.440 --> 00:51:08.320
impacting the animals.

00:51:08.320 --> 00:51:12.251
So, with that introduction, let
me start with the first case

00:51:12.251 --> 00:51:12.750
study.

00:51:12.750 --> 00:51:14.920
I want to talk about
blue whales for a minute.

00:51:14.920 --> 00:51:16.760
And blue whales, I
don't know if any of you

00:51:16.760 --> 00:51:18.801
have ever had the fortune
of seeing a blue whale,

00:51:18.801 --> 00:51:20.561
but they're awesome animals.

00:51:20.561 --> 00:51:22.560
They are the largest
animal that has ever lived.

00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:24.290
They are bigger
than any dinosaur.

00:51:24.290 --> 00:51:28.390
They can be up to 30
meters long, or 100 feet,

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:30.440
if you prefer that system.

00:51:30.440 --> 00:51:34.260
They can weigh up to 200 tons.

00:51:34.260 --> 00:51:36.120
It's a massive, massive thing.

00:51:36.120 --> 00:51:39.175
And we find them across
all of the world's oceans.

00:51:39.175 --> 00:51:41.550
They are migratory animals,
like most of the other baleen

00:51:41.550 --> 00:51:42.230
whales.

00:51:42.230 --> 00:51:47.150
They spend winters in kind of
lower latitudes, warmer waters,

00:51:47.150 --> 00:51:50.204
mating and breeding and they
travel to higher latitude

00:51:50.204 --> 00:51:52.370
regions that are more
productive and they feed there

00:51:52.370 --> 00:51:54.550
during the summer.

00:51:54.550 --> 00:51:59.840
Currently, we know there's
at least three subspecies

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:01.001
of blue whales.

00:52:01.001 --> 00:52:03.000
The Antarctic blue whale
is the largest of them.

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:07.950
This is the one that's up to 100
feet long and 30 meters long.

00:52:07.950 --> 00:52:09.980
They're found around
the Antarctic continent.

00:52:09.980 --> 00:52:12.146
They were the primary target
of the whaling industry

00:52:12.146 --> 00:52:14.620
in the early 20th
century because they

00:52:14.620 --> 00:52:17.190
have a lot of blubber,
which meant a lot of oil

00:52:17.190 --> 00:52:20.290
that the whaling
industry was after.

00:52:20.290 --> 00:52:23.112
The second subspecies are
the pygmy blue whales.

00:52:23.112 --> 00:52:24.570
They're really
pygmy little things.

00:52:24.570 --> 00:52:28.320
They only are about 24
meters long, still quite

00:52:28.320 --> 00:52:30.250
substantial in weight
as well, because they

00:52:30.250 --> 00:52:31.820
tend to be shorter in stock.

00:52:31.820 --> 00:52:34.360
They have shorter
tail and longer heads.

00:52:34.360 --> 00:52:37.290
So still provide a lot of oil.

00:52:37.290 --> 00:52:40.640
They're initially found
in the Indian Ocean.

00:52:40.640 --> 00:52:45.190
So we constrain that subspecies
to that geographic region.

00:52:45.190 --> 00:52:48.150
And then finally, all
of the other blue whales

00:52:48.150 --> 00:52:50.120
in other oceans,
we just put them

00:52:50.120 --> 00:52:53.390
all in the same subspecies of
just your general blue whale.

00:52:53.390 --> 00:52:56.130
Now the reason why
I study blue whales

00:52:56.130 --> 00:52:58.500
is that they actually
are very vocal.

00:52:58.500 --> 00:53:02.800
They produce songs that
are quite distinct.

00:53:02.800 --> 00:53:06.340
They're very low frequency,
kind of low pitched songs

00:53:06.340 --> 00:53:07.810
and they're very loud.

00:53:07.810 --> 00:53:10.400
They can travel over
very long distances.

00:53:10.400 --> 00:53:13.980
And about 10 years ago,
Mark McDonald and colleagues

00:53:13.980 --> 00:53:19.560
offered this hypothesis
that the different songs

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:21.820
that blue whales sing
in different populations

00:53:21.820 --> 00:53:25.610
might actually indicate
separate populations.

00:53:25.610 --> 00:53:27.360
Rather than having
these three subspecies,

00:53:27.360 --> 00:53:29.110
we might think of it in a
little bit finer scales.

00:53:29.110 --> 00:53:30.750
Because we know that even
though I said that they're

00:53:30.750 --> 00:53:33.426
found in all the world's
oceans, they are really distinct

00:53:33.426 --> 00:53:34.800
populations in
places where we do

00:53:34.800 --> 00:53:36.400
and we don't see blue whales.

00:53:36.400 --> 00:53:39.520
And so this map shows
that information

00:53:39.520 --> 00:53:42.280
based on these different
songs of blue whales

00:53:42.280 --> 00:53:45.710
where we know and
see them occurring.

00:53:45.710 --> 00:53:48.890
And so for example,
off the coast

00:53:48.890 --> 00:53:51.420
of California,
Washington, and Oregon,

00:53:51.420 --> 00:53:53.030
there is one
population that moves

00:53:53.030 --> 00:53:55.705
from Central America up
to Southern California

00:53:55.705 --> 00:53:58.165
and up the Gulf of
Alaska seasonally.

00:53:58.165 --> 00:53:59.790
There is also another
population that's

00:53:59.790 --> 00:54:02.430
more kind of in the Central
and Western Pacific.

00:54:02.430 --> 00:54:04.932
There's a population of blue
whales offshore here as well.

00:54:04.932 --> 00:54:06.390
But then in the
Southern hemisphere

00:54:06.390 --> 00:54:08.765
we have a couple of different
populations in the Southern

00:54:08.765 --> 00:54:10.810
Indian Ocean and one
in the Northern Indian.

00:54:10.810 --> 00:54:13.220
And then this
Antarctic blue whale

00:54:13.220 --> 00:54:16.970
that is the largest
of them all down

00:54:16.970 --> 00:54:18.900
circumpolarly around Antarctica.

00:54:18.900 --> 00:54:22.626
And so, let me play for you
a couple of their songs,

00:54:22.626 --> 00:54:25.000
because I want to demonstrate
to you how they're actually

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:25.520
very different.

00:54:25.520 --> 00:54:26.350
So you'll be able to hear them.

00:54:26.350 --> 00:54:28.640
Now actually to hear them,
I had to speed them up.

00:54:28.640 --> 00:54:30.500
Like I said, they're
very, very low pitched.

00:54:30.500 --> 00:54:31.890
They're below our hearing.

00:54:31.890 --> 00:54:34.770
But I've sped all of
these songs four times,

00:54:34.770 --> 00:54:40.196
which means that they are
four times higher frequency.

00:54:40.196 --> 00:54:41.237
So that's the first part.

00:54:41.237 --> 00:54:43.860
[SOFT BEEPING SOUND]

00:54:43.860 --> 00:54:47.927
And four times shorter
duration, so they're

00:54:47.927 --> 00:54:49.635
really faster than
they would be usually.

00:54:56.150 --> 00:54:57.570
So this up here
is a spectrogram.

00:54:57.570 --> 00:55:00.640
That's a way that we represent
kind of visually sounds.

00:55:00.640 --> 00:55:04.130
And it's time on the x-axis
and frequency on the y-axis.

00:55:04.130 --> 00:55:06.570
So that first pulsing
bit is this right here

00:55:06.570 --> 00:55:09.190
and then the tone
is the second part.

00:55:09.190 --> 00:55:13.050
So that is our North
East Pacific Blue Whale.

00:55:13.050 --> 00:55:15.050
Just for comparison,
let me play to you

00:55:15.050 --> 00:55:19.486
the blue whales as they
sound off of Australia.

00:55:19.486 --> 00:55:21.478
[WHOOSHING, HUMMING SOUND]

00:55:29.446 --> 00:55:31.890
And again, these are
sped up four times

00:55:31.890 --> 00:55:33.360
like the previous
ones, so you can

00:55:33.360 --> 00:55:35.068
hear there's a different
pattern to them.

00:55:35.068 --> 00:55:36.790
[HUMMING SOUND]

00:55:41.690 --> 00:55:44.140
So now we're having
a little bit of gap.

00:55:44.140 --> 00:55:46.100
[LOW HUMMING SOUND]

00:55:52.470 --> 00:55:56.340
I want to also play for you
the Antarctic blue whale calls.

00:55:56.340 --> 00:55:59.080
And so here it's harder
to see them here.

00:55:59.080 --> 00:56:02.030
But these little blips
down here, they're

00:56:02.030 --> 00:56:03.330
Antarctic blue whale calls.

00:56:03.330 --> 00:56:06.740
You'll notice they look a
lot less complex than some

00:56:06.740 --> 00:56:07.710
of these other ones.

00:56:07.710 --> 00:56:09.330
And they're also
much lower frequency.

00:56:09.330 --> 00:56:11.300
So you will have a really
hard time hearing these,

00:56:11.300 --> 00:56:13.216
even though again, they're
sped up four times.

00:56:20.370 --> 00:56:23.590
It's much simpler,
and quite a bit lower.

00:56:23.590 --> 00:56:26.695
So like I said, these
songs, as far as we know,

00:56:26.695 --> 00:56:29.070
we believe that they're produced
primarily or exclusively

00:56:29.070 --> 00:56:29.700
by males.

00:56:29.700 --> 00:56:31.640
We know that it's true
for the blue whales

00:56:31.640 --> 00:56:34.540
off the Northeast in
the Northeast Pacific.

00:56:34.540 --> 00:56:37.580
So we're assuming they have
some sort of a mating function.

00:56:37.580 --> 00:56:42.500
But the details are of that
a still a little bit unsure.

00:56:42.500 --> 00:56:45.839
Now that I've introduced
you to the whale songs,

00:56:45.839 --> 00:56:47.880
I want to tell you a little
bit about the whaling

00:56:47.880 --> 00:56:51.980
and the management of
whales kind of worldwide,

00:56:51.980 --> 00:56:54.860
because I think it's a very
interesting and informative

00:56:54.860 --> 00:56:55.934
story.

00:56:55.934 --> 00:56:57.600
So, the International
Whaling Commission

00:56:57.600 --> 00:56:59.110
is the international
organization

00:56:59.110 --> 00:57:04.630
that was founded in 1946, when
the whale populations worldwide

00:57:04.630 --> 00:57:08.150
were in heavy declines with the
goal of managing the whaling so

00:57:08.150 --> 00:57:10.860
that they can continue
whaling for a long time.

00:57:10.860 --> 00:57:14.840
And as their system
of management,

00:57:14.840 --> 00:57:17.130
they had a quota system
where each country,

00:57:17.130 --> 00:57:19.420
each whaling country was
assigned a certain number

00:57:19.420 --> 00:57:20.474
of blue whale units.

00:57:20.474 --> 00:57:22.640
Now, a blue whale unit is
a very interesting measure

00:57:22.640 --> 00:57:25.580
because it's a measure
of how much oil you

00:57:25.580 --> 00:57:26.700
get from the whale.

00:57:26.700 --> 00:57:30.160
And so one blue whale
unit was one blue whale

00:57:30.160 --> 00:57:34.041
or it was a two fin whales, 2
and 1/2 humpbacks, or six sei

00:57:34.041 --> 00:57:34.540
whales.

00:57:34.540 --> 00:57:37.235
So each country would get a
certain number of blue whale

00:57:37.235 --> 00:57:39.610
units, and they could catch
it in any kind of combination

00:57:39.610 --> 00:57:41.260
of all these different species.

00:57:41.260 --> 00:57:43.470
And so what that
contributed to was

00:57:43.470 --> 00:57:50.260
quite a rapid kind of
successive depletion

00:57:50.260 --> 00:57:51.480
of all the different species.

00:57:51.480 --> 00:57:54.240
Because the whalers
could just keep going out

00:57:54.240 --> 00:57:56.630
and collecting
whatever they found.

00:57:56.630 --> 00:57:59.320
But as the blue whales were
becoming more and more rare,

00:57:59.320 --> 00:58:01.028
whenever they found
one, they would still

00:58:01.028 --> 00:58:03.660
catch it, because it was
quite valuable to catch them.

00:58:03.660 --> 00:58:06.020
Until finally in
1966, their numbers

00:58:06.020 --> 00:58:09.320
had dropped so much that they
became protected worldwide.

00:58:09.320 --> 00:58:12.370
It took another 20 years for
a global whaling moratorium

00:58:12.370 --> 00:58:14.740
to come into place, because
all of the populations

00:58:14.740 --> 00:58:15.750
kept decreasing.

00:58:15.750 --> 00:58:18.260
And since then the
IWC has been tasked,

00:58:18.260 --> 00:58:20.500
not just with
management of whaling,

00:58:20.500 --> 00:58:23.430
but also has expanded its
mission to conservation

00:58:23.430 --> 00:58:25.860
of whales themselves.

00:58:25.860 --> 00:58:28.600
So currently, one
of the major things

00:58:28.600 --> 00:58:30.780
that they are
interested in working on

00:58:30.780 --> 00:58:35.400
is stock assessment as
a part of understanding

00:58:35.400 --> 00:58:38.110
of how the populations are
recovering post whaling.

00:58:38.110 --> 00:58:41.760
But then also to be able to do
this kind of stock assessment,

00:58:41.760 --> 00:58:44.670
we really need to know a lot
more about the population

00:58:44.670 --> 00:58:46.040
structure of animals.

00:58:46.040 --> 00:58:49.740
So over the years, they go
through different species

00:58:49.740 --> 00:58:52.180
and different stocks and
try to understand and use

00:58:52.180 --> 00:58:56.150
the available scientific
information to delineate

00:58:56.150 --> 00:59:00.430
and then get a better sense
of how to properly assess

00:59:00.430 --> 00:59:02.960
these stocks and populations.

00:59:02.960 --> 00:59:06.690
And so the current focus are
the pygmy blue whales, so

00:59:06.690 --> 00:59:11.150
these smaller, chubbier
Southern hemisphere animals.

00:59:11.150 --> 00:59:13.276
And just last week,
I was actually

00:59:13.276 --> 00:59:15.900
at the meeting of the scientific
committee of the International

00:59:15.900 --> 00:59:19.980
Whaling Commission where a
large variety of scientists

00:59:19.980 --> 00:59:22.305
were brought in to
provide information

00:59:22.305 --> 00:59:26.810
and all kind of best known
available science on genetics

00:59:26.810 --> 00:59:29.430
and acoustics of these
two species to try

00:59:29.430 --> 00:59:33.520
is to help form a picture of
how these populations look.

00:59:33.520 --> 00:59:36.750
So what I'm showing you here,
the map on the bottom, this

00:59:36.750 --> 00:59:38.930
is the map of all
the locations where

00:59:38.930 --> 00:59:42.190
genetic samples, so basically
tissues of blue whales

00:59:42.190 --> 00:59:44.520
are available to do
genetic analysis,

00:59:44.520 --> 00:59:48.546
to compare genetic difference
between the pygmy blue whales.

00:59:48.546 --> 00:59:49.920
And so there's a
lot of data that

00:59:49.920 --> 00:59:52.460
were collected off of Chile.

00:59:52.460 --> 00:59:55.330
In the Indian Ocean, there
are some of Madagascar, South

00:59:55.330 --> 00:59:57.510
Africa, a little
bit here of India,

00:59:57.510 --> 01:00:01.790
but most samples really come
from waters off Australia.

01:00:01.790 --> 01:00:06.620
And when doing
meta data analysis,

01:00:06.620 --> 01:00:12.660
they just found that the
populations in the Indian Ocean

01:00:12.660 --> 01:00:16.070
and off Chile are actually
as different from each other

01:00:16.070 --> 01:00:19.280
as this pygmy blue whale that I
told you, the subspecies exist

01:00:19.280 --> 01:00:20.980
that is from the
Indian Ocean, is

01:00:20.980 --> 01:00:22.560
from the Antarctic subspecies.

01:00:22.560 --> 01:00:26.480
So there is genetic evidence to
say that the Chilean population

01:00:26.480 --> 01:00:28.890
should be its own subspecies.

01:00:28.890 --> 01:00:31.400
But then we also
looked at acoustics

01:00:31.400 --> 01:00:34.620
and how do the different
acoustic stocks map

01:00:34.620 --> 01:00:36.540
into this genetic variability?

01:00:36.540 --> 01:00:38.270
And what we find--
so again, this

01:00:38.270 --> 01:00:41.520
is now a map of all the places
where different blue whale

01:00:41.520 --> 01:00:43.960
songs were recorded in
the Southern hemisphere.

01:00:43.960 --> 01:00:47.610
And different symbols
are different song types.

01:00:47.610 --> 01:00:50.300
And you'll see that there
is actually a lot more data

01:00:50.300 --> 01:00:53.140
that we have than they've
had in the genetic data.

01:00:53.140 --> 01:00:56.950
And what we have found
is that-- so this

01:00:56.950 --> 01:00:59.830
is an update of the work that
McDonald and colleagues did

01:00:59.830 --> 01:01:01.110
before.

01:01:01.110 --> 01:01:03.140
And we have found that
in a lot of these places,

01:01:03.140 --> 01:01:05.140
their initial maps and
hypotheses were actually

01:01:05.140 --> 01:01:08.410
pretty good in terms of where
the animals occur that sing

01:01:08.410 --> 01:01:09.790
these particular songs.

01:01:09.790 --> 01:01:13.400
But then interestingly,
here off Chile,

01:01:13.400 --> 01:01:15.430
we do have two different
song types that

01:01:15.430 --> 01:01:18.000
occur at the same times
and places at all times,

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.660
and they match that
genetic population

01:01:20.660 --> 01:01:23.180
that is distinct from
the Indian Ocean.

01:01:23.180 --> 01:01:25.410
But based on our data
in the Indian Ocean,

01:01:25.410 --> 01:01:28.240
we have at least three
different populations,

01:01:28.240 --> 01:01:30.350
acoustic populations,
if you will for now.

01:01:30.350 --> 01:01:33.990
So there is the turquoise
diamonds, the red triangles,

01:01:33.990 --> 01:01:37.060
and the red triangles is that
an Australian song, and then

01:01:37.060 --> 01:01:39.532
the yellow crosses.

01:01:39.532 --> 01:01:41.490
There's also this little
other diamond up here,

01:01:41.490 --> 01:01:43.810
but that is a new song
type that hasn't quite

01:01:43.810 --> 01:01:46.820
been confirmed if it's a blue
whale or not but likely is.

01:01:46.820 --> 01:01:49.860
And what you can see when you
map the places and times when

01:01:49.860 --> 01:01:52.850
these different songs occur, is
that Eastern and Western Indian

01:01:52.850 --> 01:01:56.600
Ocean songs are distinct and
occur at different places.

01:01:56.600 --> 01:01:59.910
Northern Indian song is
also different from them,

01:01:59.910 --> 01:02:02.010
and it's also
spatially separated.

01:02:02.010 --> 01:02:04.070
And there's this area in
the Central Indian Ocean

01:02:04.070 --> 01:02:06.190
where there is some
overlap between the songs.

01:02:06.190 --> 01:02:08.940
But Northern Indian Ocean song
is never there at the same time

01:02:08.940 --> 01:02:10.960
when the Southern
songs are there.

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:15.480
And so what the geneticists have
said, seeing this information

01:02:15.480 --> 01:02:18.780
is, well OK, we really don't
have very much data here

01:02:18.780 --> 01:02:20.670
from the Western Indian Ocean.

01:02:20.670 --> 01:02:22.470
But based on this
information so far,

01:02:22.470 --> 01:02:25.710
we have reason to think that the
population of Australia and off

01:02:25.710 --> 01:02:27.550
of Madagascar
could be different.

01:02:27.550 --> 01:02:29.420
So one of the outcomes
of the meeting

01:02:29.420 --> 01:02:32.110
is for a recommendation
that was put forward

01:02:32.110 --> 01:02:33.960
that there should be
more data collected,

01:02:33.960 --> 01:02:37.024
genetic data collected, in
the Western Indian Ocean

01:02:37.024 --> 01:02:38.440
so that the
comparison of genetics

01:02:38.440 --> 01:02:41.370
can be done between these
two populations to see if

01:02:41.370 --> 01:02:44.440
and how different
they actually are.

01:02:44.440 --> 01:02:49.070
At the same time, it was also
useful for the acoustics people

01:02:49.070 --> 01:02:52.300
in the crowd to talk to
geneticists, because what

01:02:52.300 --> 01:02:54.680
we found-- from
genetic data also

01:02:54.680 --> 01:02:57.470
they found of the
animals off of Australia

01:02:57.470 --> 01:03:00.470
and New Zealand in
the small samples

01:03:00.470 --> 01:03:03.970
that they currently have, there
aren't genetic differences

01:03:03.970 --> 01:03:05.834
necessarily that are obvious.

01:03:05.834 --> 01:03:07.500
And when you talk to
geneticists they'll

01:03:07.500 --> 01:03:09.470
give you different answers
to how strongly they

01:03:09.470 --> 01:03:12.190
believe that indicates
that those are really

01:03:12.190 --> 01:03:15.890
indeed same populations
or same substocks.

01:03:15.890 --> 01:03:19.290
But geneticists have
actually really good ways

01:03:19.290 --> 01:03:22.020
of looking quantitatively
at difference

01:03:22.020 --> 01:03:24.930
between the DNA of animals.

01:03:24.930 --> 01:03:27.240
And what we have done
so far as a community,

01:03:27.240 --> 01:03:28.799
as an acoustics
community, is look

01:03:28.799 --> 01:03:31.090
at more of the differences
in song in a qualitative way

01:03:31.090 --> 01:03:33.050
to delineate these
different things.

01:03:33.050 --> 01:03:34.940
So by working with
geneticists, there's

01:03:34.940 --> 01:03:37.437
hope that we can develop
more quantitative tools

01:03:37.437 --> 01:03:39.520
to compare how different
these songs actually are.

01:03:39.520 --> 01:03:41.912
Because if you remember when
I played you these songs,

01:03:41.912 --> 01:03:43.370
a couple of them
were very similar.

01:03:43.370 --> 01:03:46.300
And some of these songs here
in the Southern hemisphere,

01:03:46.300 --> 01:03:47.860
they're quite similar
to each other.

01:03:47.860 --> 01:03:50.070
But they're very different
from the Antarctic song,

01:03:50.070 --> 01:03:52.150
and they're very different from
some of the Northern hemisphere

01:03:52.150 --> 01:03:52.840
songs.

01:03:52.840 --> 01:03:55.460
So if we can measure
the amount of difference

01:03:55.460 --> 01:03:58.490
in songs of different
populations,

01:03:58.490 --> 01:04:01.150
we could also form
more refined hypotheses

01:04:01.150 --> 01:04:02.900
and how likely they
are to actually

01:04:02.900 --> 01:04:05.810
be difference of populations.

01:04:05.810 --> 01:04:07.840
So that's kind of a
large scale story.

01:04:07.840 --> 01:04:11.290
On a finer scale
story, by looking

01:04:11.290 --> 01:04:13.830
at some of the song variability
in the North Pacific,

01:04:13.830 --> 01:04:17.270
we have found that even one song
that we thought was the same

01:04:17.270 --> 01:04:19.120
may be not quite true.

01:04:19.120 --> 01:04:22.230
So here I'm showing you,
this is the first song

01:04:22.230 --> 01:04:24.660
that I played you, the
tonal part of it in Southern

01:04:24.660 --> 01:04:27.940
California and off of Alaska
that we record regularly.

01:04:27.940 --> 01:04:30.840
And by visual
inspection, if you've

01:04:30.840 --> 01:04:33.140
seen enough of
these at least, it

01:04:33.140 --> 01:04:35.530
becomes apparent that there
is this little kink here

01:04:35.530 --> 01:04:37.900
in the Gulf of Alaska
song, where the frequencies

01:04:37.900 --> 01:04:39.450
get kind of steps down a bit.

01:04:39.450 --> 01:04:42.080
And so when we looked at this
in a little bit more detail,

01:04:42.080 --> 01:04:44.740
we found that in
fact-- so this is now

01:04:44.740 --> 01:04:47.630
from many measured calls
in the Gulf of Alaska

01:04:47.630 --> 01:04:50.640
and Southern California over
a couple of different years.

01:04:50.640 --> 01:04:53.710
We find that, in fact, the
step in the Gulf of Alaska

01:04:53.710 --> 01:04:56.650
is much more prominent than
it is in Southern California.

01:04:56.650 --> 01:04:59.280
But the question is, is
that really important

01:04:59.280 --> 01:05:01.450
and how does it
matter to the whales?

01:05:01.450 --> 01:05:03.620
Now we don't quite
know that yet.

01:05:03.620 --> 01:05:07.410
But what we do see is in
addition to this step-- now

01:05:07.410 --> 01:05:10.340
I've put this in
the same y axis here

01:05:10.340 --> 01:05:13.200
and you'll notice that this
call is much higher frequency

01:05:13.200 --> 01:05:14.110
than that call.

01:05:14.110 --> 01:05:16.610
It's about one and one
half Hertz difference,

01:05:16.610 --> 01:05:18.840
which may seem trivial.

01:05:18.840 --> 01:05:21.430
However, we know that
blue whales actually

01:05:21.430 --> 01:05:23.700
slowly over time are
decreasing their frequency.

01:05:23.700 --> 01:05:26.580
Their calls are getting
lower and lower pitched.

01:05:26.580 --> 01:05:29.960
And the difference between
these two call types

01:05:29.960 --> 01:05:32.960
is about eight years
of frequency shift.

01:05:32.960 --> 01:05:36.610
So that makes me think that
these guys are actually

01:05:36.610 --> 01:05:38.530
separate and they're
not necessarily

01:05:38.530 --> 01:05:42.030
communicating with each other,
at least in the same way.

01:05:42.030 --> 01:05:46.940
So I think we've made
some good progress

01:05:46.940 --> 01:05:50.770
in using these large scale
distinctions in a song

01:05:50.770 --> 01:05:52.729
to get some idea of
population variability.

01:05:52.729 --> 01:05:54.270
But we're really
getting to the point

01:05:54.270 --> 01:05:57.070
where we can think of some
finer scale differences

01:05:57.070 --> 01:06:02.310
and how much difference in
population they may imply.

01:06:02.310 --> 01:06:04.060
Also does this
particular [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:04.060 --> 01:06:09.520
I told you about Northeast
Pacific song difference is

01:06:09.520 --> 01:06:12.120
interesting or relevant
because we have known

01:06:12.120 --> 01:06:13.830
that the global
population of California

01:06:13.830 --> 01:06:15.620
has been stable for
the last 20 years

01:06:15.620 --> 01:06:18.911
or so, which is not quite what
people expect because they're

01:06:18.911 --> 01:06:21.160
supposed to be increasing
and recovering from whaling.

01:06:21.160 --> 01:06:24.470
And one of the ongoing
questions is, why are they not?

01:06:24.470 --> 01:06:28.660
And it's possible that they're
expanding their range, which

01:06:28.660 --> 01:06:31.410
is kind of the going
hypothesis as they're just

01:06:31.410 --> 01:06:32.800
moving to different areas.

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:34.590
But these differences
in songs may

01:06:34.590 --> 01:06:36.717
indicate that that's not
entirely the whole story,

01:06:36.717 --> 01:06:38.675
that it might be something
else going on there,

01:06:38.675 --> 01:06:41.540
that these maybe are somehow
different populations.

01:06:41.540 --> 01:06:43.510
So the next challenge
for us is going

01:06:43.510 --> 01:06:46.707
to be to figure out how to use
these acoustics to actually do

01:06:46.707 --> 01:06:47.540
abundance estimates.

01:06:47.540 --> 01:06:50.300
This is one thing that's really
important for the managers,

01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:53.930
both from the Navy perspective
but also in the International

01:06:53.930 --> 01:06:56.660
Whaling Commission
community to be

01:06:56.660 --> 01:07:01.320
able to enhance the application
of these data further.

01:07:01.320 --> 01:07:05.870
So next, I'm going to
shift gears altogether,

01:07:05.870 --> 01:07:09.950
and I want to talk about another
group of animals that is just

01:07:09.950 --> 01:07:11.920
as commercially
important, and I would

01:07:11.920 --> 01:07:14.455
argue, maybe close to
being as charismatic,

01:07:14.455 --> 01:07:17.740
which are groupers.

01:07:17.740 --> 01:07:20.010
They are really charismatic.

01:07:20.010 --> 01:07:21.480
Nassau grouper for
example, they're

01:07:21.480 --> 01:07:23.310
famous for being very friendly.

01:07:23.310 --> 01:07:25.432
Divers love them, because
if you go on a reef,

01:07:25.432 --> 01:07:26.390
they'll come up to you.

01:07:26.390 --> 01:07:27.550
They're this huge fish.

01:07:27.550 --> 01:07:29.591
It's an impressive experience
if you ever had it.

01:07:29.591 --> 01:07:32.430
It's as impressive as it is to
see a blue whale in the ocean.

01:07:32.430 --> 01:07:34.596
it's just as impressive to
have a giant fish come up

01:07:34.596 --> 01:07:35.990
to your face and say hello.

01:07:35.990 --> 01:07:37.240
[INAUDIBLE]

01:07:37.240 --> 01:07:40.260
They're about five, I
think, five, six feet long.

01:07:40.260 --> 01:07:43.440
They can be pretty a big fish.

01:07:43.440 --> 01:07:46.090
And so, they're ecologically
important on reefs

01:07:46.090 --> 01:07:48.680
because they are
voracious predators.

01:07:48.680 --> 01:07:52.900
They are the top down
control to the reefs.

01:07:52.900 --> 01:07:56.230
They're commercially important
because they're very tasty.

01:07:56.230 --> 01:07:58.140
And they also have
this recreational value

01:07:58.140 --> 01:08:00.000
because people like
seeing them on the reefs

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:01.985
and like swimming with them.

01:08:01.985 --> 01:08:03.360
There's a number
of other species

01:08:03.360 --> 01:08:06.190
of groupers that are common,
found through the Atlantic

01:08:06.190 --> 01:08:08.050
and in the reefs
of the Atlantic.

01:08:08.050 --> 01:08:12.280
But many of groupers, they
have this unfortunate spawning

01:08:12.280 --> 01:08:15.905
behavior where fish from all
around will come and aggregate

01:08:15.905 --> 01:08:19.529
in one place at a very
predictable time, every year,

01:08:19.529 --> 01:08:21.235
same place, same time to spawn.

01:08:21.235 --> 01:08:22.609
They will make
these aggregations

01:08:22.609 --> 01:08:25.575
of thousands of fish,
which then make them very

01:08:25.575 --> 01:08:26.700
susceptible to overfishing.

01:08:26.700 --> 01:08:29.189
Because if you're a fisherman,
you know the fish are there,

01:08:29.189 --> 01:08:30.920
you drop your hook
and line and you

01:08:30.920 --> 01:08:34.620
can decimate that population
in a matter of days.

01:08:34.620 --> 01:08:39.319
Now luckily for me, these
guys make also lots of sounds.

01:08:39.319 --> 01:08:42.100
So let me show you
what they sound like.

01:08:42.100 --> 01:08:44.570
[CLICKING AND GROANING SOUNDS]

01:08:52.773 --> 01:08:54.189
So that was a Red
hind group where

01:08:54.189 --> 01:08:57.005
they very common in
the site in the Caymans

01:08:57.005 --> 01:08:58.046
where we've been working.

01:08:58.046 --> 01:09:01.350
[CLICKING AND GROANING SOUNDS]

01:09:01.350 --> 01:09:02.350
That's a Nassau grouper.

01:09:02.350 --> 01:09:05.460
They're a little bit grumpier.

01:09:05.460 --> 01:09:08.990
So, what we have been doing
in the last couple of years

01:09:08.990 --> 01:09:12.540
is working on
Little Cayman, this

01:09:12.540 --> 01:09:14.170
is actually a very
special place,

01:09:14.170 --> 01:09:18.080
where a new, well new
to humans, aggregation,

01:09:18.080 --> 01:09:21.109
spawning aggregation was
discovered in the early 2000s.

01:09:21.109 --> 01:09:23.729
So the Caymans are
a three island chain

01:09:23.729 --> 01:09:26.149
in the middle of the
Caribbean, just South of Cuba.

01:09:26.149 --> 01:09:29.010
And Little Cayman is
the smallest of them.

01:09:29.010 --> 01:09:31.370
And here on the west
side, in early 2000s,

01:09:31.370 --> 01:09:34.760
the fishermen discovered a
previously unknown spawning

01:09:34.760 --> 01:09:35.590
aggregation.

01:09:35.590 --> 01:09:36.960
They started fishing it hard.

01:09:36.960 --> 01:09:38.279
The numbers plummeted.

01:09:38.279 --> 01:09:40.840
Caymanian government
however, stepped in,

01:09:40.840 --> 01:09:44.069
stopped fishing, and
started encouraging research

01:09:44.069 --> 01:09:48.180
in this location to
learn more about how

01:09:48.180 --> 01:09:50.430
we can protect these
animals so that we

01:09:50.430 --> 01:09:54.130
can have sustainable fishery
and keep them under reefs.

01:09:54.130 --> 01:09:57.890
And in the time since, in
the last 10 or 12 years,

01:09:57.890 --> 01:09:59.740
the Grouper Moon
Project has been

01:09:59.740 --> 01:10:01.400
composed of a
variety of scientists

01:10:01.400 --> 01:10:04.290
who have gone out and
done numerous dives

01:10:04.290 --> 01:10:07.310
on and around the spawning site
to study more and understand

01:10:07.310 --> 01:10:10.070
better the spawning
biology, the interchange

01:10:10.070 --> 01:10:12.100
of different populations
and things like that.

01:10:12.100 --> 01:10:14.850
We joined them a
year and a half ago

01:10:14.850 --> 01:10:18.930
and put recorders down,
because prior to us

01:10:18.930 --> 01:10:22.910
joining the-- so the
groupers spawn at dusk.

01:10:22.910 --> 01:10:25.700
And the divers would go down,
observe spawning events,

01:10:25.700 --> 01:10:27.040
but then it would get dark.

01:10:27.040 --> 01:10:29.940
So we didn't really
know how much longer.

01:10:29.940 --> 01:10:31.927
Does the spawning just
happen during that time?

01:10:31.927 --> 01:10:33.260
What did the fish do afterwards?

01:10:33.260 --> 01:10:34.330
Did they disperse?

01:10:34.330 --> 01:10:36.210
Are they still in the
same spot on the reef?

01:10:36.210 --> 01:10:40.380
Kind of the dynamics of the
movements were highly unknown.

01:10:40.380 --> 01:10:43.870
So we put a number of
recorders at the site,

01:10:43.870 --> 01:10:47.670
had all kinds of misfortunes
and adventures in doing so.

01:10:47.670 --> 01:10:49.760
But we've had some
really exciting data

01:10:49.760 --> 01:10:51.950
and really interesting things.

01:10:51.950 --> 01:10:54.290
And this is mostly work
that my student, Casey,

01:10:54.290 --> 01:10:56.710
has been pushing through on.

01:10:56.710 --> 01:10:58.680
And so one of the
approaches that we took

01:10:58.680 --> 01:11:01.710
is using what's called
soundscape analysis, which

01:11:01.710 --> 01:11:03.510
is kind of this large
scale of looking

01:11:03.510 --> 01:11:07.260
at the whole spectrum of sounds,
and trying to divide it up

01:11:07.260 --> 01:11:10.330
into different bands
that are of interest.

01:11:10.330 --> 01:11:13.159
And so what she has done,
you can see here again,

01:11:13.159 --> 01:11:14.950
these are spectrograms
of different grouper

01:11:14.950 --> 01:11:16.450
sounds in the top panel.

01:11:16.450 --> 01:11:18.260
And you can see
there's a lot of energy

01:11:18.260 --> 01:11:21.917
in most of these calls up
the few hundred Hertz range.

01:11:21.917 --> 01:11:24.500
Once you get lower, even though
there's a lot of call activity

01:11:24.500 --> 01:11:26.666
there as well there's a lot
of anthropogenic sounds.

01:11:26.666 --> 01:11:30.250
So she was looking for a
fine balance between the two.

01:11:30.250 --> 01:11:33.950
And then at higher frequency,
we get a lot of other fish

01:11:33.950 --> 01:11:36.650
sounds, a lot of naturally
squirrel fish, which

01:11:36.650 --> 01:11:38.480
are quite abundant on the reef.

01:11:38.480 --> 01:11:40.240
And so what she has
done is gone through

01:11:40.240 --> 01:11:41.780
and measured five
minutes and then

01:11:41.780 --> 01:11:44.150
one hour averages
of sound levels

01:11:44.150 --> 01:11:46.550
for these two frequency
bands over the times

01:11:46.550 --> 01:11:48.240
of our whole deployments.

01:11:48.240 --> 01:11:52.000
And first what we looked
at is how do the fish daily

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:54.710
soundscape change
during the first period

01:11:54.710 --> 01:11:56.770
we had recorders out in 2015.

01:11:56.770 --> 01:11:59.680
So just as a cue, I'm using
a little picture of Nassau,

01:11:59.680 --> 01:12:04.080
as the Serranidae as the
grouper band descripter

01:12:04.080 --> 01:12:07.510
and then this is our
little squirrel fish that

01:12:07.510 --> 01:12:09.660
is representing other fish.

01:12:09.660 --> 01:12:13.140
And so on these plots, this
is about six days of data,

01:12:13.140 --> 01:12:16.900
the gray shaded boxes
represent nighttime.

01:12:16.900 --> 01:12:19.220
And what you can see
there is the blue

01:12:19.220 --> 01:12:21.560
is the five minute
averages, and the black

01:12:21.560 --> 01:12:22.990
is the one hour averages.

01:12:22.990 --> 01:12:25.820
So you see there's a lot
of variability from five

01:12:25.820 --> 01:12:27.220
minute to five minute interval.

01:12:27.220 --> 01:12:29.650
But when you sum
over that, there

01:12:29.650 --> 01:12:35.519
is a bit of a nocturnal
peak just at about sunset.

01:12:35.519 --> 01:12:37.560
But I should also point
out that during this year

01:12:37.560 --> 01:12:40.830
at this particular site, Nassau
grouper spawning occurred

01:12:40.830 --> 01:12:43.600
on these two nights, and then
back here in these last three

01:12:43.600 --> 01:12:46.120
nights, it was tiger
grouper spawning period.

01:12:46.120 --> 01:12:48.370
And you can see that during
the tiger spawning grouper

01:12:48.370 --> 01:12:52.890
particular, there is a little
bit stronger signals because we

01:12:52.890 --> 01:12:55.140
actually had more tiger
grouper on our particular site

01:12:55.140 --> 01:12:56.100
this year.

01:12:56.100 --> 01:12:58.452
But you see some of
these daily patterns.

01:12:58.452 --> 01:12:59.910
Same is true for
the squirrel fish,

01:12:59.910 --> 01:13:02.290
but they have a very
clear corpuscular pattern

01:13:02.290 --> 01:13:07.740
with peaks at dusk and dawn
and relatively lower levels

01:13:07.740 --> 01:13:09.230
during the day.

01:13:09.230 --> 01:13:11.800
Now in addition to the
daily cycle in calls,

01:13:11.800 --> 01:13:17.080
there's also changes
in the local activity

01:13:17.080 --> 01:13:18.460
with lunar phase.

01:13:18.460 --> 01:13:20.740
Spawning often happens,
or generally happens,

01:13:20.740 --> 01:13:25.770
sometime around usually a
few days after a new moon.

01:13:25.770 --> 01:13:30.220
And so here I'm showing
six days at a period

01:13:30.220 --> 01:13:33.400
in between the moon phases.

01:13:33.400 --> 01:13:37.340
This plot is the new moon and
this plot shows the full moon

01:13:37.340 --> 01:13:38.260
time period.

01:13:38.260 --> 01:13:41.180
And what I just want you
to take home from this

01:13:41.180 --> 01:13:43.600
is that the average level,
so basically average noise

01:13:43.600 --> 01:13:48.260
of this band of grouper sounds
is substantially higher.

01:13:48.260 --> 01:13:51.710
Two to three DB, while it
doesn't sound much this

01:13:51.710 --> 01:13:53.130
is a logarithmic scale.

01:13:53.130 --> 01:13:56.810
So it's actually quite
a substantial increase

01:13:56.810 --> 01:13:58.770
during the new and full moons.

01:13:58.770 --> 01:14:00.740
So the animals are
a lot more active

01:14:00.740 --> 01:14:03.470
during those other times.

01:14:03.470 --> 01:14:08.570
We found the same pattern for
the squirrel fish as well.

01:14:08.570 --> 01:14:10.400
But then what we
really want to know

01:14:10.400 --> 01:14:13.340
is, do these metrics
actually represent fish?

01:14:13.340 --> 01:14:18.450
Can we certainly say that these
are fish that we are detecting?

01:14:18.450 --> 01:14:20.860
And so what Casey has
done is gone through

01:14:20.860 --> 01:14:24.020
and logged painfully all
of the calls that have

01:14:24.020 --> 01:14:26.770
occurred over those six days.

01:14:26.770 --> 01:14:31.810
And that was about 20,000
calls that she's gone through.

01:14:31.810 --> 01:14:33.490
They're basically
identified by species.

01:14:33.490 --> 01:14:36.500
A lot of them are Red hinds,
but we have quite a variety

01:14:36.500 --> 01:14:37.900
of animals in there.

01:14:37.900 --> 01:14:41.520
And the blue line here
in both of these plots

01:14:41.520 --> 01:14:44.680
show the number of
calls at any given hour.

01:14:44.680 --> 01:14:47.410
And then the black is still
the soundscape metric.

01:14:47.410 --> 01:14:52.380
And you'll notice, when doing
cross correlations in these,

01:14:52.380 --> 01:14:55.990
you see that [INAUDIBLE] are
relationship between the two.

01:14:55.990 --> 01:14:58.080
So there is some
indication that they

01:14:58.080 --> 01:15:01.930
are good proxies, these metrics
that you can compute rapidly

01:15:01.930 --> 01:15:03.590
are good proxies.

01:15:03.590 --> 01:15:05.480
Specifically here
during the time

01:15:05.480 --> 01:15:07.680
when we had peak
tiger spawning period,

01:15:07.680 --> 01:15:12.610
you can see that these
increases in number of calls

01:15:12.610 --> 01:15:14.460
match quite nicely
with increases

01:15:14.460 --> 01:15:16.293
with our acoustic level,
so we're definitely

01:15:16.293 --> 01:15:20.090
do a good job measuring
tiger grouper presence.

01:15:20.090 --> 01:15:22.577
But so in addition, while
we had all these calls, what

01:15:22.577 --> 01:15:24.660
I didn't mention right
away is that we didn't just

01:15:24.660 --> 01:15:25.701
have one recorder either.

01:15:25.701 --> 01:15:27.190
We had multiple recorders.

01:15:27.190 --> 01:15:30.570
We had up to four
to five recorders

01:15:30.570 --> 01:15:32.710
simultaneously
collecting this data

01:15:32.710 --> 01:15:39.040
in an array that was about
50 meter by 50 meter large.

01:15:39.040 --> 01:15:41.750
And so what you can
do when you have

01:15:41.750 --> 01:15:43.850
that kind of a
setup is if you hear

01:15:43.850 --> 01:15:46.030
the same sound of
multiple instruments,

01:15:46.030 --> 01:15:49.040
you can use the
difference in the time

01:15:49.040 --> 01:15:52.760
of the arrival of that same
signal to multiple locations

01:15:52.760 --> 01:15:55.440
to localize where the sound
is actually coming from.

01:15:55.440 --> 01:15:58.250
And so the process
then consists basically

01:15:58.250 --> 01:16:00.620
of finding the
sound of interest,

01:16:00.620 --> 01:16:03.690
doing some acoustic processing
where you filter it,

01:16:03.690 --> 01:16:05.520
you rectify the
signal, and then you

01:16:05.520 --> 01:16:09.550
do cross-correlation between
the two pairs of instruments.

01:16:09.550 --> 01:16:12.560
And you look for the
time delay and the peak

01:16:12.560 --> 01:16:14.110
of that cross-correlation.

01:16:14.110 --> 01:16:15.840
And that gives you
the time delay.

01:16:15.840 --> 01:16:19.460
And you'll notice here,
this is time in seconds.

01:16:19.460 --> 01:16:21.640
So our peak is just slightly
off or off from zero.

01:16:21.640 --> 01:16:23.200
So this is a small array.

01:16:23.200 --> 01:16:26.580
We're looking at very,
very small time differences

01:16:26.580 --> 01:16:29.160
because we are localizing
in a very small time scale.

01:16:29.160 --> 01:16:33.220
But what you get once you have
this time delay with any two

01:16:33.220 --> 01:16:36.760
instruments, what that gives
you is this hyperbolic solution.

01:16:36.760 --> 01:16:40.520
So it's a hyperbola along which
that sound may have occurred.

01:16:40.520 --> 01:16:43.140
And then if you
have multiple pairs,

01:16:43.140 --> 01:16:45.000
you get multiple
hyperbole, and where

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:47.760
they cross that is where
your sound is occurring.

01:16:47.760 --> 01:16:50.890
So what Casey's is in
the process of doing then

01:16:50.890 --> 01:16:54.420
is overlaying the locations
of all these different sounds

01:16:54.420 --> 01:16:57.680
that we can localize
on a map that was

01:16:57.680 --> 01:17:00.230
collected of habitat quality.

01:17:00.230 --> 01:17:05.460
So what I'm showing you
here, the black triangles

01:17:05.460 --> 01:17:08.010
are the instrument
recorder locations.

01:17:08.010 --> 01:17:10.360
And then the circles
of different colors

01:17:10.360 --> 01:17:11.660
are calls of different species.

01:17:11.660 --> 01:17:13.868
There are different call
types for different species.

01:17:13.868 --> 01:17:16.260
All the blue ones are the
Nassau and tiger calls.

01:17:16.260 --> 01:17:18.594
The red, there's a couple
of them, are the Red hind.

01:17:18.594 --> 01:17:20.260
There's also some
black grouper and some

01:17:20.260 --> 01:17:22.320
that we haven't identified
the species yet.

01:17:22.320 --> 01:17:25.030
And so you see there is
quite a few calls that

01:17:25.030 --> 01:17:25.940
have occurred here.

01:17:25.940 --> 01:17:29.910
And then underneath it, this
is the bottom, the reef.

01:17:29.910 --> 01:17:33.030
And the lighter areas
are sandy patches

01:17:33.030 --> 01:17:37.500
and then these darker parts are
coral or other hard structure.

01:17:37.500 --> 01:17:39.250
So what we're in
the process now,

01:17:39.250 --> 01:17:42.070
just kind of qualitatively
looking at this,

01:17:42.070 --> 01:17:45.170
it appears of these
intersections or kind

01:17:45.170 --> 01:17:49.890
of borderline between sand
and rough reef structure maybe

01:17:49.890 --> 01:17:51.400
really important habitat.

01:17:51.400 --> 01:17:54.760
We're in the process of
actually quantifying those call

01:17:54.760 --> 01:17:57.240
localizations and seeing
what kind of habitat

01:17:57.240 --> 01:18:00.080
different calling occurs on.

01:18:00.080 --> 01:18:03.350
So to sum up, I hope
I've convince you

01:18:03.350 --> 01:18:05.680
that acoustics can be
a really powerful tool

01:18:05.680 --> 01:18:10.520
to help us learn more about the
biology, distribution, ecology

01:18:10.520 --> 01:18:12.790
of a variety of marine animals.

01:18:12.790 --> 01:18:15.145
In particular though,
what we're finding is

01:18:15.145 --> 01:18:17.350
it's going to be very
important to understand

01:18:17.350 --> 01:18:19.600
the context of these
different calls

01:18:19.600 --> 01:18:25.482
to really go further in bringing
that context into management

01:18:25.482 --> 01:18:27.440
perspective understanding
better where and when

01:18:27.440 --> 01:18:30.470
and why the different
animals are occurring.

01:18:30.470 --> 01:18:32.780
And then I think what's
going to be important also

01:18:32.780 --> 01:18:35.080
is to continue, there's
been a lot of advances

01:18:35.080 --> 01:18:41.361
on the hardware
side and of things.

01:18:41.361 --> 01:18:43.110
But I think the future
advances are really

01:18:43.110 --> 01:18:45.080
coming in our ability
to process this data

01:18:45.080 --> 01:18:46.450
and interpret this data.

01:18:46.450 --> 01:18:48.577
And I think using
qualitative tools

01:18:48.577 --> 01:18:50.410
and combining techniques
of different fields

01:18:50.410 --> 01:18:51.701
is going to be crucial to that.

01:18:51.701 --> 01:18:53.740
So I think that's the
next exciting thing.

01:18:53.740 --> 01:18:56.290
So with that, I want to
acknowledge the funding

01:18:56.290 --> 01:18:58.255
agencies and all the
collaborators and students

01:18:58.255 --> 01:18:59.713
and I thank you
for your attention.

