-I have a question
for each speaker.

01:19:24.736 --> 01:19:25.261
Is that OK?

01:19:25.261 --> 01:19:25.760
-Yeah.

01:19:25.760 --> 01:19:28.540
-So first, Rachel,
I was just wondering

01:19:28.540 --> 01:19:31.270
you're advocating and
planning for transitioning

01:19:31.270 --> 01:19:36.330
from hard shoreline protection
to living coastline.

01:19:36.330 --> 01:19:40.490
How are you factoring
in the anticipated rise

01:19:40.490 --> 01:19:42.200
in ocean level?

01:19:42.200 --> 01:19:45.600
-Yeah, so it will
depend on where

01:19:45.600 --> 01:19:48.290
you're considering
doing living shorelines

01:19:48.290 --> 01:19:49.490
versus hard shorelines.

01:19:49.490 --> 01:19:54.060
And I will say at first, I think
we'll have a hybrid approach

01:19:54.060 --> 01:19:54.650
everywhere.

01:19:54.650 --> 01:19:57.867
So places like New
York City or Miami

01:19:57.867 --> 01:19:59.700
where you have a lot
of hard infrastructure,

01:19:59.700 --> 01:20:02.050
you're going to need some
engineering structures

01:20:02.050 --> 01:20:03.480
like floodgates.

01:20:03.480 --> 01:20:06.010
You're going to need
seawalls in some places.

01:20:06.010 --> 01:20:09.210
And the idea is to kind of
integrate the living components

01:20:09.210 --> 01:20:11.610
in with the hard infrastructure
for these really heavily

01:20:11.610 --> 01:20:16.205
urbanized areas that are going
to see a lot of sea level rise,

01:20:16.205 --> 01:20:17.790
like Miami.

01:20:17.790 --> 01:20:21.350
In some areas where we
expect in the next 100 years

01:20:21.350 --> 01:20:24.280
there to be enough for
the area to be underwater,

01:20:24.280 --> 01:20:28.800
we're essentially trying to plan
for that retreat, in the sense

01:20:28.800 --> 01:20:31.410
that a lot of these
living designs

01:20:31.410 --> 01:20:35.230
put the hard structure
seaward of the habitat

01:20:35.230 --> 01:20:38.820
they're trying to protect,
so that as you the sea

01:20:38.820 --> 01:20:41.590
level rises, those
habitats, those marshes,

01:20:41.590 --> 01:20:43.800
could actually migrate
landward without having

01:20:43.800 --> 01:20:45.960
a hard structure behind them.

01:20:45.960 --> 01:20:49.020
So that's one way that the
living shoreline approach,

01:20:49.020 --> 01:20:51.910
particularly with the off
shore kind of protection

01:20:51.910 --> 01:20:55.930
is factoring in sea
level, is that assuming

01:20:55.930 --> 01:20:58.080
that those habitats
can migrate like they

01:20:58.080 --> 01:21:00.430
would if you didn't
have any development.

01:21:00.430 --> 01:21:04.690
But again that's also assuming
that the rates of sea level

01:21:04.690 --> 01:21:07.020
don't increase too rapidly.

01:21:07.020 --> 01:21:11.055
So we still have-- there's a
lot of new research right now

01:21:11.055 --> 01:21:16.800
on using dredge material to
actually deposit sediment

01:21:16.800 --> 01:21:18.840
onto marshes like in
the Gulf Coast's that

01:21:18.840 --> 01:21:20.930
are sediment starved
and are actually sinking

01:21:20.930 --> 01:21:23.660
as sea level is rising
to help them keep up

01:21:23.660 --> 01:21:24.910
and be able to migrate.

01:21:24.910 --> 01:21:26.690
So I think we're
going to need a lot

01:21:26.690 --> 01:21:30.980
of different-- both engineering
and ecological techniques.

01:21:30.980 --> 01:21:33.790
And it's going to be
very region specific.

01:21:33.790 --> 01:21:35.690
So a it's complicated.

01:21:35.690 --> 01:21:38.440
-The other question I had is
a question I've always had

01:21:38.440 --> 01:21:40.240
and I never had a
chance to ask it before,

01:21:40.240 --> 01:21:44.080
which is, what exactly
is it about sonar that

01:21:44.080 --> 01:21:50.030
makes it deleterious to
whales and other sea life?

01:21:50.030 --> 01:21:52.050
How specifically,
physiologically

01:21:52.050 --> 01:21:53.570
does it impact the whale?

01:21:53.570 --> 01:21:56.550
-So there's several
different types of sonar.

01:21:56.550 --> 01:22:00.150
There is the low frequency
sonar that can be anywhere.

01:22:00.150 --> 01:22:02.360
It's really usually
below the kilohertz.

01:22:02.360 --> 01:22:04.160
And the mid frequency
active sonar

01:22:04.160 --> 01:22:08.840
is the one that's been
most implicated recently

01:22:08.840 --> 01:22:12.910
in the last 16, 20
years in stranding

01:22:12.910 --> 01:22:17.390
events for [? Adonisees ?] but
really a variety of species.

01:22:17.390 --> 01:22:23.000
And it's an interesting
question because the frequencies

01:22:23.000 --> 01:22:24.830
at which those
sonars are occurring

01:22:24.830 --> 01:22:28.040
are not necessarily
the same frequencies

01:22:28.040 --> 01:22:30.960
at which the animals are
producing sound, and therefore

01:22:30.960 --> 01:22:33.210
would it be reasonable to
assume that their hearing is

01:22:33.210 --> 01:22:35.520
most sensitive.

01:22:35.520 --> 01:22:40.240
But in the cases
where we have seen

01:22:40.240 --> 01:22:43.140
impact is basically in
animals that have stranded

01:22:43.140 --> 01:22:50.490
and they've had various
internal damage in air cavities

01:22:50.490 --> 01:22:52.100
and structures of that nature.

01:22:52.100 --> 01:22:59.010
So there is presumably some
resonance in the air cavities

01:22:59.010 --> 01:23:01.460
and soft tissues
resulting from the sonar.

01:23:01.460 --> 01:23:05.590
But I mean it's a lot more
complicated I think than just

01:23:05.590 --> 01:23:08.820
direct physiological
impact often,

01:23:08.820 --> 01:23:11.520
because we certainly
know there's a variety

01:23:11.520 --> 01:23:17.680
of bathometric and other
constrains that lead to some

01:23:17.680 --> 01:23:20.490
of these events, leading to
standings and others that

01:23:20.490 --> 01:23:21.270
don't.

01:23:21.270 --> 01:23:26.570
So it's a complex answer.

01:23:26.570 --> 01:23:29.480
I'm not sure that I answered
your question satisfactorily.

01:23:29.480 --> 01:23:32.115
-These changes that you see in
the dead whales, [INAUDIBLE]

01:23:39.131 --> 01:23:39.630
-The which?

01:23:39.630 --> 01:23:40.171
I'm missing--

01:23:40.171 --> 01:23:43.770
-They die [INAUDIBLE]
They die on the beach.

01:23:43.770 --> 01:23:44.270
-Right.

01:23:44.270 --> 01:23:47.620
But so sometimes,
often they'll strand

01:23:47.620 --> 01:23:50.290
or they come on the
beach because they're

01:23:50.290 --> 01:23:53.440
disoriented or
otherwise under stress

01:23:53.440 --> 01:23:57.590
and are trying to
escape whatever,

01:23:57.590 --> 01:24:00.300
move away from whatever source
is causing them distress.

01:24:00.300 --> 01:24:05.059
So they may die from
the internal injuries,

01:24:05.059 --> 01:24:06.350
but that's not always the case.

01:24:06.350 --> 01:24:08.725
Sometimes they'll just die
from the process of stranding,

01:24:08.725 --> 01:24:11.250
where they don't want to
be in the environment that

01:24:11.250 --> 01:24:14.110
is causing them stress.

01:24:14.110 --> 01:24:15.950
-Question in the back.

01:24:15.950 --> 01:24:17.820
-Yes, Dr. Gittman.

01:24:17.820 --> 01:24:23.820
This is a question about
