01:24:23.820 --> 01:24:28.320
And I wonder what the
scientific community

01:24:28.320 --> 01:24:29.760
is going to do about this.

01:24:29.760 --> 01:24:33.660
I can hear all of the
Band-Aid approaches

01:24:33.660 --> 01:24:36.450
to dealing with
this, but my sense

01:24:36.450 --> 01:24:39.210
is that scientists
are trying to be

01:24:39.210 --> 01:24:42.790
as conservative and cautious as
they can be about the sea level

01:24:42.790 --> 01:24:44.710
rise, but it's rising.

01:24:44.710 --> 01:24:49.330
So you have at least from
the Carolinas north, just

01:24:49.330 --> 01:24:52.420
affecting the East
Coast, what will

01:24:52.420 --> 01:24:55.380
be a disaster down the
line, and band-aids

01:24:55.380 --> 01:24:57.840
aren't going to fix it.

01:24:57.840 --> 01:25:01.580
And a couple of
things there I believe

01:25:01.580 --> 01:25:04.760
it was the North
Carolina government that

01:25:04.760 --> 01:25:07.590
is in a state of
denial from hell

01:25:07.590 --> 01:25:12.470
to put it gently, much
like climate change denial.

01:25:12.470 --> 01:25:15.386
So they wouldn't
allow, what was it,

01:25:15.386 --> 01:25:18.250
a law or regulation
to go through.

01:25:18.250 --> 01:25:19.850
And I'm sure there
are one of many.

01:25:19.850 --> 01:25:23.100
I think of Miami, all
the time like this.

01:25:23.100 --> 01:25:26.840
But I can see where this is
going to be a real problem.

01:25:26.840 --> 01:25:30.710
What's your take on that, if
you want to make it public?

01:25:30.710 --> 01:25:33.820
But my real question is what
is the science community

01:25:33.820 --> 01:25:36.414
going to do because they've
got to educate people?

01:25:39.320 --> 01:25:42.190
-It is a very complicated issue.

01:25:42.190 --> 01:25:45.837
We are in a very polarized
political society right now.

01:25:45.837 --> 01:25:48.170
And I think it's gotten even
more polarized even since I

01:25:48.170 --> 01:25:50.260
started graduate school.

01:25:50.260 --> 01:25:52.180
When I started in
North Carolina,

01:25:52.180 --> 01:25:57.260
it was pre the passing of
the ban on sea level rise.

01:25:57.260 --> 01:25:59.600
And I was actually working
with the Coastal Resources

01:25:59.600 --> 01:26:01.490
Commission and with the
Division of Coastal Management

01:26:01.490 --> 01:26:02.810
and they were fairly proactive.

01:26:02.810 --> 01:26:04.820
They had a science
panel that had

01:26:04.820 --> 01:26:07.380
developed different
trajectories for sea level rise.

01:26:07.380 --> 01:26:10.640
And they were basing their
mucosal management policies

01:26:10.640 --> 01:26:12.870
on these different trajectories.

01:26:12.870 --> 01:26:15.820
And North Carolina in the '70s
was actually very progressive

01:26:15.820 --> 01:26:18.310
and they banned all shoreline
hardening on open coasts.

01:26:18.310 --> 01:26:19.980
So if you were in
North Carolina you

01:26:19.980 --> 01:26:23.550
don't see sea walls
on any of the beaches.

01:26:23.550 --> 01:26:26.120
You'll see an occasional
jetty or groin

01:26:26.120 --> 01:26:29.470
that the Army Corps built
in maybe the '40s or '50s

01:26:29.470 --> 01:26:31.900
at major inlets,
but you don't have

01:26:31.900 --> 01:26:34.916
hardening like you see in
other parts of the country.

01:26:34.916 --> 01:26:36.540
And then when I was
in graduate school,

01:26:36.540 --> 01:26:40.520
we had a change in
the political arena,

01:26:40.520 --> 01:26:44.360
and they essentially turned
over the entire Department

01:26:44.360 --> 01:26:45.400
of Natural Resources.

01:26:45.400 --> 01:26:48.430
They dismantled
the science panel.

01:26:48.430 --> 01:26:52.690
And they passed a law,
largely driven by developers,

01:26:52.690 --> 01:26:56.040
who wanted to be able to
develop in high risk areas,

01:26:56.040 --> 01:26:58.740
because it would in the short
term make them a lot of money.

01:26:58.740 --> 01:27:00.240
They said, we don't
want you to make

01:27:00.240 --> 01:27:02.530
any new law about
coastal management

01:27:02.530 --> 01:27:05.610
based on any projection
on future sea level

01:27:05.610 --> 01:27:08.630
rise it has to be based on
historic rates of sea level

01:27:08.630 --> 01:27:11.610
rise, which no climate
scientists would agree

01:27:11.610 --> 01:27:13.810
is in any way reasonable.

01:27:13.810 --> 01:27:16.870
Because the idea is that the
sea level rise is accelerating.

01:27:16.870 --> 01:27:18.250
But that was the
law they passed.

01:27:18.250 --> 01:27:21.584
And so they since have
overturned our ban

01:27:21.584 --> 01:27:23.000
on shoreline
hardening and are now

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:25.600
allowing terminal groins,
which are basically

01:27:25.600 --> 01:27:28.320
put in place where
you have developers

01:27:28.320 --> 01:27:33.980
wanting to build in extremely
dynamic, unstable inlet areas.

01:27:33.980 --> 01:27:35.870
And they want to
have these groins put

01:27:35.870 --> 01:27:39.806
in place to protect their high
risk, high dollar developments.

01:27:39.806 --> 01:27:41.930
So, yeah, North Carolina
has gone kind of backwards

01:27:41.930 --> 01:27:45.530
since I have lived there.

01:27:45.530 --> 01:27:49.410
But the scientific
community is basically

01:27:49.410 --> 01:27:51.800
trying to do a
multifaceted approach.

01:27:51.800 --> 01:27:55.700
So we obviously, in a lot
of areas, are saying retreat

01:27:55.700 --> 01:27:57.990
is going to be the only
option in the long term.

01:27:57.990 --> 01:28:00.400
I mean you're going
to have to move away.

01:28:00.400 --> 01:28:02.330
And we're a disaster
driven society.

01:28:02.330 --> 01:28:06.530
So it will likely take events
like Sandy, like Katrina,

01:28:06.530 --> 01:28:09.090
where whole communities
are going to get wiped out,

01:28:09.090 --> 01:28:12.180
and then we're going to
choose to not rebuild.

01:28:12.180 --> 01:28:14.290
And that's a very sad
way of looking at it.

01:28:14.290 --> 01:28:16.400
But I think it's the
most likely scenario,

01:28:16.400 --> 01:28:19.220
because everything we've seen
in terms of coastal management

01:28:19.220 --> 01:28:22.300
changes has been reactionary.

01:28:22.300 --> 01:28:24.890
We are seeing more funding
post-Sandy I think,

01:28:24.890 --> 01:28:26.500
for resilience efforts.

01:28:26.500 --> 01:28:29.510
Some of the major cities
like New York, Miami,

01:28:29.510 --> 01:28:34.040
are starting to think about ways
they can plan for the future.

01:28:34.040 --> 01:28:36.874
So New York has adopted
like a long term

01:28:36.874 --> 01:28:38.290
plan for how they're
going to deal

01:28:38.290 --> 01:28:40.330
with sea level
rise that includes

01:28:40.330 --> 01:28:43.280
gray and green infrastructure.

01:28:43.280 --> 01:28:45.150
There's a design
in place right now

01:28:45.150 --> 01:28:48.450
that will actually let part
of the downtown area flood

01:28:48.450 --> 01:28:53.340
naturally and then just recede
by including kind of vegetation

01:28:53.340 --> 01:28:55.870
and a series of
floodgates, and you

01:28:55.870 --> 01:29:01.370
know it'll be a combined effort
of engineering and ecology.

01:29:01.370 --> 01:29:03.980
So I think we just
try to advocate

01:29:03.980 --> 01:29:07.200
for many different solutions
in many different phases

01:29:07.200 --> 01:29:09.430
of this process.

01:29:09.430 --> 01:29:12.930
I think if you just
preach retreat,

01:29:12.930 --> 01:29:15.760
you will only reach a small
portion of the population.

01:29:15.760 --> 01:29:19.910
So the surveys I showed in the
talk were to the 850 responses,

01:29:19.910 --> 01:29:22.610
we asked the question,
how much do you

01:29:22.610 --> 01:29:24.680
think sea level is going
to rise and how do you

01:29:24.680 --> 01:29:26.120
think it will
affect your property

01:29:26.120 --> 01:29:27.910
and what are you going to do?

01:29:27.910 --> 01:29:32.750
And most people said, I
mean the range in sea level

01:29:32.750 --> 01:29:36.130
went from zero to 100 feet.

01:29:36.130 --> 01:29:39.535
I mean people have no
idea how much sea level

01:29:39.535 --> 01:29:40.450
is going to rise.

01:29:40.450 --> 01:29:44.320
And so that's one issue is
the education component.

01:29:44.320 --> 01:29:47.370
Two, even if they said
it was going to rise,

01:29:47.370 --> 01:29:49.660
I got responses of
mostly, well, it's

01:29:49.660 --> 01:29:52.250
not going affect me it's going
to affect the next generation.

01:29:52.250 --> 01:29:54.750
Because a lot of people that
live on the waterfront in North

01:29:54.750 --> 01:29:55.860
Carolina are retirees.

01:29:55.860 --> 01:29:58.340
You know, this is where they've
retired and they're like,

01:29:58.340 --> 01:30:02.090
well, you know, my grandkids
will deal with that.

01:30:02.090 --> 01:30:05.170
And then the third part of what
are they going to do about it?

01:30:05.170 --> 01:30:08.330
Overwhelmingly, most
people said nothing.

01:30:08.330 --> 01:30:10.690
And most people said they
were willing to pay over

01:30:10.690 --> 01:30:14.110
100% increase in their insurance
even with sea level rise,

01:30:14.110 --> 01:30:16.560
so they're not willing
to move either.

01:30:16.560 --> 01:30:18.970
They're going to
pay the insurance.

01:30:18.970 --> 01:30:21.700
And so one change we may see
is that the insurance companies

01:30:21.700 --> 01:30:22.760
are starting to pull out.

01:30:22.760 --> 01:30:25.670
So in the Outer Banks
in North Carolina,

01:30:25.670 --> 01:30:28.290
they won't insure whole
stretches of shoreline.

01:30:28.290 --> 01:30:30.770
You can't rebuild based
on insurance anymore.

01:30:30.770 --> 01:30:33.630
You have to be willing to build
your house with no insurance.

01:30:33.630 --> 01:30:35.420
People still do it.

01:30:35.420 --> 01:30:39.290
But it's at least moving
in that direction.

01:30:39.290 --> 01:30:45.280
So people respond to
monetary incentives I

01:30:45.280 --> 01:30:46.610
think more than anything else.

01:30:46.610 --> 01:30:49.160
And so, once we
show that it's going

01:30:49.160 --> 01:30:50.810
to cost more than
it's worth, I think

01:30:50.810 --> 01:30:54.250
we'll start to see more retreat.

01:30:54.250 --> 01:30:56.040
-Thank you.

01:30:56.040 --> 01:31:02.350
-Until 2012, I lived on a
barrier reef, Singer Island

01:31:02.350 --> 01:31:05.040
in Florida, off West Palm.

01:31:05.040 --> 01:31:09.620
And I saw all this
and all the variations

01:31:09.620 --> 01:31:14.440
that you've described of
solutions for the shore.

01:31:14.440 --> 01:31:21.960
So when I would talk to people,
you have public access legally

01:31:21.960 --> 01:31:27.120
to the ocean in Florida,
the Atlantic coast.

01:31:27.120 --> 01:31:29.090
So I say, well, we
really shouldn't

01:31:29.090 --> 01:31:33.650
be building-- it should
be like five miles inland.

01:31:33.650 --> 01:31:35.640
And of course
that's not popular.

01:31:35.640 --> 01:31:37.520
I said, OK, well,
how about three.

01:31:37.520 --> 01:31:40.470
You know, that's
not popular either.

01:31:40.470 --> 01:31:44.850
So I understand that money
is the loudest talker

01:31:44.850 --> 01:31:48.520
and has the most
seats at the table.

01:31:48.520 --> 01:31:52.090
But going back to
education, I think

01:31:52.090 --> 01:31:56.940
the only big piece that
will ever change anything

01:31:56.940 --> 01:32:02.230
is the education of the very
youngest people now alive,

01:32:02.230 --> 01:32:07.320
our children to understand
what will happen

01:32:07.320 --> 01:32:13.630
and that they're going to take
on the mantle of stewardship.

01:32:13.630 --> 01:32:16.810
And when they've lived
with that for 20 years,

01:32:16.810 --> 01:32:20.710
they might be willing
to change and make

01:32:20.710 --> 01:32:22.680
decisions that will be good.

01:32:22.680 --> 01:32:27.830
But you won't find
people now to be

01:32:27.830 --> 01:32:29.080
willing to make those changes.

01:32:29.080 --> 01:32:35.920
So you have to work at
all those levels at once

01:32:35.920 --> 01:32:39.190
in order to hope that
in a quarter century

01:32:39.190 --> 01:32:41.358
there might be real progress.

01:32:41.358 --> 01:32:43.190
-I completely agree.

01:32:43.190 --> 01:32:45.440
One thing we are
doing-- so education

01:32:45.440 --> 01:32:48.900
is a huge component of
the work that we do.

01:32:48.900 --> 01:32:51.220
And we have like
demonstration projects,

01:32:51.220 --> 01:32:53.637
and you know I've done several
field trips out to a living

01:32:53.637 --> 01:32:54.136
shoreline.

01:32:54.136 --> 01:32:56.420
I showed a picture of the
oyster reef living shoreline

01:32:56.420 --> 01:32:58.570
that we constructed in 2012.

01:32:58.570 --> 01:33:02.310
And we bring-- this is part
of an estaurine research.

01:33:02.310 --> 01:33:04.275
So we bring children
out, we teach them

01:33:04.275 --> 01:33:05.400
about the living shoreline.

01:33:05.400 --> 01:33:09.056
But we're also still invested
in educating adults too.

01:33:09.056 --> 01:33:10.680
One of the big things
in North Carolina

01:33:10.680 --> 01:33:14.570
is to initiate-- this kind of
an under the radar Initiative

01:33:14.570 --> 01:33:18.504
that's mostly funded through
donations and through NGOs

01:33:18.504 --> 01:33:20.670
and not obviously through
our legislature right now,

01:33:20.670 --> 01:33:24.760
but is to start a
green engineering

01:33:24.760 --> 01:33:26.480
or like living
shoreline certification

01:33:26.480 --> 01:33:30.460
program for marine contractors
and engineering firms.

01:33:30.460 --> 01:33:33.130
And that's mainly because
your average homeowner

01:33:33.130 --> 01:33:36.520
will buy waterfront
property, see that's eroding,

01:33:36.520 --> 01:33:37.930
and not know what
to do about it.

01:33:37.930 --> 01:33:40.340
And they'll just look up,
they'll go into Google

01:33:40.340 --> 01:33:43.640
and find a coastal engineering
firm or a contractor,

01:33:43.640 --> 01:33:47.260
call them and say, my shoreline
is eroding, what do I do?

01:33:47.260 --> 01:33:49.780
And your average
contractor has been putting

01:33:49.780 --> 01:33:51.200
in bulkheads for three decades.

01:33:51.200 --> 01:33:52.400
And they say, well,
this is what you need.

01:33:52.400 --> 01:33:53.520
You need a bulkhead.

01:33:53.520 --> 01:33:55.430
And they say that because that's
what they know how to build

01:33:55.430 --> 01:33:57.390
and that's what's going
to cost the most money.

01:33:57.390 --> 01:33:59.389
And it also actually costs
the most maintenance,

01:33:59.389 --> 01:34:01.160
but they're not going
to tell them that.

01:34:01.160 --> 01:34:04.160
And so now I've participated
in two training sessions

01:34:04.160 --> 01:34:07.260
for real estate developers,
landscape architects, and then

01:34:07.260 --> 01:34:09.050
engineering and
contracting firms

01:34:09.050 --> 01:34:11.930
on how to build
living shorelines

01:34:11.930 --> 01:34:14.010
and how it could
potentially make them money.

01:34:14.010 --> 01:34:18.640
Because they could go back
and help maintain the plants.

01:34:18.640 --> 01:34:22.060
They can basically get free
advertising through the state,

01:34:22.060 --> 01:34:24.220
because they'll have
the certification.

01:34:24.220 --> 01:34:26.370
So there are ways
that we're trying

01:34:26.370 --> 01:34:28.700
to reach some of
the key players,

01:34:28.700 --> 01:34:31.640
but it's a slow process.

01:34:31.640 --> 01:34:34.110
Again, people are
resistant to change.

01:34:34.110 --> 01:34:37.080
But I'm still optimistic.

01:34:37.080 --> 01:34:39.480
OK, we can take a
break in a second.

01:34:39.480 --> 01:34:43.360
But I have the opportunity
to ask one question.

01:34:43.360 --> 01:34:44.960
I wanted to ask Anna.

01:34:44.960 --> 01:34:49.740
So I will confess to be being
something of a language maven.

01:34:49.740 --> 01:34:51.510
I'm not an expert
in linguistics,

01:34:51.510 --> 01:34:54.720
but I'm always interested
in languages and how they

01:34:54.720 --> 01:34:57.030
evolve and change in humans.

01:34:57.030 --> 01:35:01.450
And what struck me was, when
you were talking about the whale

01:35:01.450 --> 01:35:04.430
populations, I
was just wondering

01:35:04.430 --> 01:35:08.570
in the back of my mind,
do they learn their songs?

01:35:08.570 --> 01:35:12.660
And is there an evolution
over time and location

01:35:12.660 --> 01:35:15.985
the same way you would see
different language populations

01:35:15.985 --> 01:35:17.410
in humans on Earth?

01:35:17.410 --> 01:35:20.130
Does that sound right?

01:35:20.130 --> 01:35:23.990
-Yes, so there are several
examples now that we've seen.

01:35:23.990 --> 01:35:28.430
In humpback whales, songs change
over time and they evolve.

01:35:28.430 --> 01:35:30.870
And we have seen now
that in some there

01:35:30.870 --> 01:35:33.450
is an example off
of Australia where

01:35:33.450 --> 01:35:40.190
there was a new animal that came
to the East Coast of Australia,

01:35:40.190 --> 01:35:42.240
singing the Western
Australia song.

01:35:42.240 --> 01:35:43.920
And within two
seasons, everybody

01:35:43.920 --> 01:35:46.990
adopted the new songs.

01:35:46.990 --> 01:35:49.990
Clearly it was better.

01:35:49.990 --> 01:35:51.940
But then there's
also this gradual--

01:35:51.940 --> 01:35:55.800
-The hip, new whales
the cool new whale.

01:35:55.800 --> 01:35:57.780
-Exactly, and also
humpback song is really

01:35:57.780 --> 01:36:00.460
the one that's been most
looked at in studies.

01:36:00.460 --> 01:36:03.430
We know there a kind of a
cultural transmission of song

01:36:03.430 --> 01:36:06.800
across the Pacific from
the West to the East,

01:36:06.800 --> 01:36:09.804
where it's been progressively
changing and moving its way.

01:36:09.804 --> 01:36:11.220
But recently,
actually some of the

01:36:11.220 --> 01:36:13.280
work that I'm doing
with colleagues,

01:36:13.280 --> 01:36:17.900
we're finding that fin
whales, which they actually

01:36:17.900 --> 01:36:24.330
have very similar pattern of
the sound that they produce.

01:36:24.330 --> 01:36:26.950
It's just this very
short, down sweep,

01:36:26.950 --> 01:36:30.050
but the pattern in
which they produce them,

01:36:30.050 --> 01:36:32.340
they're very, very
regularly repeated.

01:36:32.340 --> 01:36:34.040
It's almost like a metronome.

01:36:34.040 --> 01:36:37.540
And what we have found
is that in some places,

01:36:37.540 --> 01:36:41.430
they'll have these songs change
or the pattern of the intervals

01:36:41.430 --> 01:36:48.270
changes across the year, where
it starts relatively fast,

01:36:48.270 --> 01:36:51.040
and then gradually gets slower
and slower across the mating

01:36:51.040 --> 01:36:51.840
season.

01:36:51.840 --> 01:36:55.220
And so, all the fin whales
across the North Pacific

01:36:55.220 --> 01:36:56.980
do the same thing,
the same pattern.

01:36:56.980 --> 01:37:00.080
They start at the same rate
and then they all together

01:37:00.080 --> 01:37:01.394
get slower and slower.

01:37:01.394 --> 01:37:03.310
And then in Southern
California just recently,

01:37:03.310 --> 01:37:06.629
we've seen that they've
actually changed their song.

01:37:06.629 --> 01:37:08.420
And now it's a completely
different pattern

01:37:08.420 --> 01:37:09.878
that just slowly,
gradually there's

01:37:09.878 --> 01:37:12.150
no longer the seasonal
cycle, but over time it's

01:37:12.150 --> 01:37:13.620
getting slower and slower.

01:37:13.620 --> 01:37:19.260
So there clearly is some
transmission and exchange

01:37:19.260 --> 01:37:22.930
between these
different populations,

01:37:22.930 --> 01:37:26.418
but we don't really know a
whole lot about how that works.

01:37:26.418 --> 01:37:27.290
-Fascinating.

01:37:27.290 --> 01:37:29.800
OK, so let's thank
our speakers again.

01:37:29.800 --> 01:37:32.850
[APPLAUSE]

